<HEADLINE> Iraqi Paper Urges Normalization of Iraqi-French Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 17 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi government newspaper
today urged France to consider "more seriously" the normalization
of relations with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Al-Thawra, organ of the Iraqi ruling Arab Baath Socialist
Party, said Iraq can forgive France's hostile acts against it
since the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
But it expressed the hope that France can "rectify" its
strategic mistake so that France's role in the Gulf War would be
seen as "merely a mistake" made by former French President
Francois Mitterrand.
</P>
<P>
Any hesitation by France to mend fences would show that France
might commit the same mistake and harm Arabs through Iraq, the
newspaper added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the newspaper made an attack on France for its
reported decision not to treat President Saddam Hussein's eldest
son, Odai, who was wounded in an attempt on his life last month
here.
</P>
<P>
Iraq severed diplomatic ties with France six years ago. Now the
Iraqi authorities eagerly want to restore their friendly
relationship to the level in the 1980s and lift the
U.N. six-year-old embargo imposed for its 1990 invasion of Kuwait
with the help of France, a permanent member of the U.N. Security
Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
