<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Hydro-electric Power Generation Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's hydro-electric power
source, Lake Kariba, is at a critically low level for power
generation, the Zimbabwe Electricity Supply Authority (ZESA) said
today.
</P>
<P>
"The water situation in Lake Kariba remains critical with
water flows over Victoria Falls having dropped to less than 100
cubic meters per second, the lowest flow levels ever recorded
since records began in 1907," the ZESA said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"With the water level in Lake Kariba at this level, it
presents a serious challenge to the Zambezi River Authority (ZRA)
which manages the waters of the mighty river on behalf of Zambia
and Zimbabwe regarding the water allocation," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Lake Kariba is the world's largest man-made lake. Its flow
rate just picked up with recent rains.
</P>
<P>
A meeting is due to be held on Friday between the ZRA, ZESA and
Zambia Electricity Supply Corporation (ZESCO) to discuss power
allocation for the period from February 1 to July 31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
