<HEADLINE> Locusts No Longer Problem in Zimbabwe This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Di Taylor, an entomologist of
the Commercial Farmers Union of Zimbabwe, said today the menacing
red locust has disappeared in the most areas of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Taylor said the locusts are no longer moving in swarms as
before, but are scattered all over thus posing no threat to
crops.
</P>
<P>
"They are no very much spread out and the situation is far
much better than what it was this time last year," said Taylor.
</P>
<P>
She said a South African expert on locust has been working to
fight the insects in Mozambique, where they are believed to have
originated from.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's farmers lost crops worth millions of Dollars from
the red locusts last year and there are fears that there would
more damage this year once they are allowed to breed in large
numbers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
