<HEADLINE> Solana, Kinkel Discuss NATO-Russia Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 17 (Xinhua) -- On the eve of his Moscow visit,
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) Secretary-General Javier
Solana held talks in Bonn today with German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel on the eastward expansion of the military alliance and its
relations with Russia.
</P>
<P>
According to German Foreign Ministry, both Solana and Kinkel
stressed at the meeting that NATO should make an agreement with
Russia on the issue of NATO's eastward expansion before the
alliance's Madrid summit this July.
</P>
<P>
At the forthcoming summit, NATO will nominate the first group
of countries in Central and Eastern Europe as candidates for the
Western alliance's expansion.
</P>
<P>
Solana said NATO should seek consensus with Russia on the basis
of a strong, stable and sustained security partnership. He also
expressed confidence in an "enlarged NATO" in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kinkel promised to give "full support" to Solana's
Moscow visit next week, saying Germany will continue its efforts
to allay Russia's fear over the NATO enlargement.
</P>
<P>
The minister reiterated that Germany aimed to draw in Russia as
"a partner with equal rights" to the construction of "a new
European security architecture."
</P>
<P>
He recalled his proposal for a special "NATO-Russia charter,"
under which Russia will be allowed to discuss matters of common
concern as an equal partner in a permanent consultation committee
of NATO.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel said he himself would be visiting Moscow in a few weeks
for talks on the issue with his Russian counterpart Yevgeni
Primakov. The latter will in turn send an envoy to Bonn within
this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
