<HEADLINE> US Industrial Production Up 0.8 Percent in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January (Xinhua) -- U.S. industrial production
increased by 0.8 percent in December for the second straight month
and rose by 3.2 percent for all of 1996, the U.S. Federal Reserve
(Fed) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Fed said that December's production of durable goods
-- items such as cars and computers expected to last more than
three years -- shot up by 1.3 percent, stronger than the 0.9
percent gain in November.
</P>
<P>
Nondurable goods output was up 0.8 percent after increasing 0.5
percent a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing output jumped by 1.1 percent in December, up from
0.7 percent a month earlier. Production at mines surged 1.2
percent, double the 0.6 percent gain in November.
</P>
<P>
But utility output plunged by 3.3 percent, more than erasing a
2.3 percent advance a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
The Fed report supports other data showing inflation under
control. It said that the U.S. industries were operating at 83.8
percent of capacity, up from 83.4 percent in November. It was the
highest rate since it reached 83.9 percent in August 1995.
</P>
<P>
However, that is still less than the 85 percent capacity
utilization which analysts say would result in the production
bottlenecks that could lead to shortages in the labor market and
higher prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
