<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Industry Fully Liberalized in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Major reform measures in
Kenya's coffee industry have been announced over the past months
to accelerate commercial competitiveness of the industry with
minimal state control.
</P>
<P>
Last October, the Kenyan government announced major changes in
the management of the coffee industry, which would lead to its
full liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the changes, then Agriculture Minister Simeon
Nyachae said that the coffee growers are given power to elect
directors who in turn will pick a chairman and choose a chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
Previously, the Kenyan law empowered the agriculture minister
to appoint a chairman and a chief executive from among the
directors.
</P>
<P>
The government will withdraw from the Coffee Board of Kenya
(CBK), which was set up by the government to manage the coffee
industry, so that it can become purely a farmers' organization.
</P>
<P>
In a circular issued last November, the Kenyan government
announced that the Central Coffee Auction, which had been adopted
for the coffee industry in the past, is converted into a coffee
exchange to facilitate the fixing of reserve prices and balloting
for floor auctioneers.
</P>
<P>
CBK General Manager Aggrey Murunga described the move as a
further step in the liberalization of the coffee industry, which
is the main earner of foreign exchange in the east African
country.
</P>
<P>
The coffee production in the country in the past three
years increased by 28 percent from 75,516 tons in 1993-94 to
97,575 tons in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
However, coffee output is estimated to fall in the 1996-97
crop year and some officials of the industry projected the output
at 85,000 tons, because of bad weather and diseases.
</P>
<P>
Last year Kenya earned 16.36 billion Kenyan Shillings (about
300 million U.S. Dollars) by exporting 110,000 tons of coffee,
compared with 14.4 billion Shillings in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
