<HEADLINE> Turkey Seeks Foreign Cooperation in Tank-building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Foreign arms manufacturers are
invited to join a 4.5-billion-U.S.-dollar project of upgrading the
world's fourth largest tank fleet in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, Turkey will produce 800 main battle tanks of
the third generation for its armed forces to meet the next
century's defense needs, local newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Turkish military sources as saying that these
tanks would have higher maneuver ability, higher firing power as
well as lower weight.
</P>
<P>
"In the long run, the number of the tanks under this project
will reach 2,500," the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Four Turkish companies would be invited to bid for the project,
but any bidding Turkish company is required to find a foreign
partner which has experience in tank production, according to the
planned tender
</P>
<P>
The project is likely to kick off at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The project will greatly enhance Turkish armed forces' combat
capacity, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The 780,000-strong Turkish troops is among the 10 largest
armies in the world, and its tank unit ranks fourth in the world,
according to the World Strategic Information Institute.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Turkey has given priority to army
modernization programs and new weapons introduction.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Chief of General Staff of the Turkish Armed Forces
Ismail Hakki Karadayi announced that 150 billion dollars would be
needed for the arms and operation of the Turkish armed forces in
the next 25 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
