<HEADLINE> 240 Million Kg of Tobacco Expected in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe now expects to produce
240 million kg of tobacco, up from the original forecast of 230
million kg made last year, the Zimbabwe Tobacco Association (ZTA)
said here today.
</P>
<P>
ZTA Public Relations Director Lal Taylor said all indications
pointed to another record crop, with many farmers now either
completing curing or reaping the early irrigated crop.
</P>
<P>
She said the area planted with the irrigated crop had been
doubled, mainly due to the availability of surface water
following an unusually heavy rain season during 1995/96.
</P>
<P>
The ZTA has agreed that tobacco output should increase
gradually every year by at least 10 percent so as to meet rising
demand on the world market, she added.
</P>
<P>
"Indications are that demand is still there throughout the
world and we are hoping to meet that demand from our particularly
quality crop," she said.
</P>
<P>
Taylor said, "We have had a good season and we are now
preparing for the opening of the auction floors on April 22."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe last season produced about 201 million kg, which were
expected to earn the country about 600 million U.S. Dollars in
foreign currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
