<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nine Liberians Killed in Ambush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- At least nine people were killed
and three others wounded in Monrovia, capital of Liberia, when
unidentified gunmen ambushed a vehicle Thursday morning,
according to a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Some of the victims are identified as militiamen of the ethnic
wing of the United Liberation Movement of Liberia (ULIMO-J) led
by Roosevelt Johnson.
</P>
<P>
So far, nobody has declared responsible for the ambush, which
might be connected with the on-going disarmament exercise in that
war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Disarmament and demobilization of Liberia's estimated 60,000
factional fighters started on November 22 last year and only
about 7,000 of them put down their weapons two weeks before the
January 31 deadline.
</P>
<P>
The slow pace of disarmament is partly attributed to the delay
in the release of additional troops to the west African
peacekeeping force, known as ECOMOG, by some countries in the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The lack of enthusiasm and cooperation of factional leaders is
also a major factor.
</P>
<P>
The program has been further jeopardized by recent calls from
two warlords for another peace conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
