<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kurdish Leader: PUK to Cut Ties With PKK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan (PUK) leader Jalal Talabani said here today his party
will cut ties with the Turkish outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party
(PKK).
</P>
<P>
Talabani said at a press conference:" We have no confidence in
them (PKK)," adding that there were two PKK camps in northern
Iraq, which was under his party's control.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 12-year-old guerrilla war for
self-rule in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The PUK will not let any Kurdish group to have a military base
in northern Iraq and stage attacks against neighboring countries,
said Talabani.
</P>
<P>
"I also want Turkey to allow the transportation of
humanitarian aid of non-governmental organizations to northern
Iraq," said the PUK leader.
</P>
<P>
Talabani arrived here Thursday for the exchange of views
with Turkish officials on the situation in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iran-backed PUK fought with the Kurdish Democratic Party
(KDP), supported by President Saddam Hussein, in late August of
last year, which led to U.S. air strike against Iraqi military
targets.
</P>
<P>
The PUK and the KDP then signed a peace deal on October 31,
1996 under mediation of the United States, Britain and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The northern Iraq has been occupied by Kurdish rebels since
the Gulf War in 1991, but it split into rival zones after
the KDP and the PUK began fighting each other in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
