<HEADLINE> Greek, Cypriot Presidents Meet in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Greek President Kostis
Stephanopoulos met today with his Cyprus counterpart, Glafcos
Clerides, for an exchange of views on the entire spectrum of
issues relating to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Neither president made any statement after the 40-minute
meeting which was attended also by Cyprus Foreign Minister Alekos
Michailides and other senior Cypriot officials.
</P>
<P>
Delegations from Cyprus and Greece are scheduled to meet this
evening, chaired jointly by Clerides and Greek Prime Minister
Costas Simitis, to examine all the aspects of the Cyprus problem
in view of the initiative which Washington has said it will be
undertaking.
</P>
<P>
Clerides' visit to Athens came in the wake of Turkish threats
to take military action if the missiles are deployed on the
island.
</P>
<P>
Clerides, who arrived Thursday on a three-day visit, reiterated
upon his arrival however that the Russian anti-aircraft missiles
bought by his country will definitely be deployed on the
war-divided island.
</P>
<P>
"There is no question that the missiles will not be deployed,"
the president said.
</P>
<P>
Greece, which has signed a joint defense agreement with Cyprus,
has warned that any Turkish action against the island will spark a
Greek-Turkish war. 
</P>
