<BODY>
<HEADLINE> America Online Boosts Network Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The America Online Inc., beset
by complaints from customers frustrated by its overloaded service,
said it will trim its advertisement campaign and spend an extra
100 million U.S. dollars beefing up its network to handle its
higher traffic load.
</P>
<P>
Since the company adopted a plan of 19.95 dollars a month for
unlimited use last December, the number of customers has swelled
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
It's just like an "eat as you can" plan, which has hooked
people on-line as long as they wish, some analysts said. Because
of the difficulty to login, many people stay on line even while
away for dinner. Members now spend an average of about half an
hour a day on-line, compared with just 14 minutes a few months
ago. Similar situation has occurred with other Internet service
providers such as Prodigy and Microsoft Net (MSN).
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal reported today that by pulling its new
television ads and cutting back on direct-marketing efforts, AOL
hopes to slow an influx of new members and reduce the strain on
its network, which has greeted thousands of members with slow
response time and busy signals.
</P>
<P>
The largest on-line company now boasts more than 8 million
members, with 1.2 million new comers in the most recent quarter.
Its network can handle a maximum of about 260,000 users on-line at
any given time. Last fall its usage peaked at about 140,000
customers at the same time. But member complaints about the
crowded network have become widespread. Over the past couple of
days, the company had to cut its capacity for hours to fix its
facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
