<HEADLINE> EU to Take Legal Action Against Ireland on Overgrazing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) is to
take legal action against Ireland over the country's failure to
monitor the environmental damage done by sheep overgrazing,
according to well-informed sources.
</P>
<P>
The action, which is taken under the EU Rome Treaty, is part of
a wider set of legal proceedings against Ireland for failing to
protect ecologically sensitive areas.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that all EU-funded grants are paid on the basis
that no other EU law is contravened and no environmental damage is
done.
</P>
<P>
One EU source was quoted as saying recently that the Irish
Department of Agriculture "hasn't policed this at all."
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Agriculture Ministry said that "we've
received nothing formally" regarding EU legal action against
Ireland, but "we have heard something is happening and we're
sitting on the edge of our seats."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that Irish Agriculture Minister Ivan Yates
announced a package of financial measures to lessen the problem of
sheep overgrazing in sensitive mountain areas in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Under the measures, the Irish government gave generous cash
payments to those farmers who agreed to reduce sheep numbers on
the hills.
</P>
<P>
However, some Irish environmental groups have been drawing
attention to the widespread damage being done to blanket bog and
to other sensitive upland habitats by sheep overgrazing.
</P>
<P>
Following their complaints and some independent investigations,
the EU Commission has initialed a wider legal action over
Ireland's alleged failure to assess the environmental impact of
intensive farming projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
