<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Lags Behind Competitors in Basic Maths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Britain lags far behind in an
international basic maths test, with only half the success rate of
the Japanese and French and young adults considerably worse than
people over 45, according to a survey by the Basic Skills Agency.
</P>
<P>
The survey, of a total of almost 6,000 people in seven
industrialized countries, found that only 20 percent of British
adults could correctly work out 12 "common, everyday"
calculations.
</P>
<P>
Japan topped the numeracy table with 43 percent of respondents
answering every question correctly, followed by France (40
percent), Holland (38), Denmark (36), Sweden (34) and Australia
(33). Britain came bottom.
</P>
<P>
Among the British sample of 1,000 adults, women performed worse
than men and 16- to 24-year-olds did much worse than those over 45,
with 16 percent answering all questions correctly compared with 29
percent of the older age group.
</P>
<P>
Another survey also published by the agency, a charity that
encourages adult education, found that numeracy had a significant
and sustained impact on adults' lives, and especially their
chances in the labor market.
</P>
<P>
It showed that men with poor numeracy were more likely to be
unemployed or in manual jobs while women were more likely to be in
part-time work.
</P>
<P>
Alan Wells, the agency's director, said that Britain's poor
performance was not just a recent problem.
</P>
<P>
"But to start climbing the table we need to raise expectations
and aspirations, stop expecting and accepting low standards and
motivate people to want to learn and improve," he added.
</P>
<P>
Gillian Shephard, the education and employment secretary,
welcomed the campaign and promised to announce more initiatives
later this month to tackle poor adult basic skills. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
