<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Continue Arms Deal with Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's major
state arms producer, DENEL, said here today that there is no
question of an arms deal with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman of the company Paul Holtzhausen said in a statement
that the DENEL gave a demonstration of its tank-firing control
system in Syria last year.
</P>
<P>
But he said Syria has given no firm commitment to buying the
system, costing about 638 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
He denies having asked permission from the National Arms
Coordinating Committee of the South African parliament to export
the system to Syria.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said his company only asked for a permit to
market its Tiger tank-firing control system in Syria, which was
granted at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The arms deal has sparked a diplomatic row between South
Africa and the United States, which accuses Syria of supporting
international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The DENEL was formed in the early 1990s as a private company
to take over control of South African arms industry from the
ARMSCOR, which is a government controlled group.
</P>
<P>
South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said early this
week that the cabinet did "conditionally agree" to sell Syria the
tank-firing control system last month, but a final decision will
not be made until the end of this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
