<HEADLINE> Greek PM Opposes Farmers' New Protest Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis today expressed strong opposition to a renewed protest
action announced by farmers, likening it to blackmail.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in parliament during a scheduled debate on
agricultural policy, Simitis said the protest action constituted a
blow to the country's fragile economy and society and harmed the
interests of farmers themselves.
</P>
<P>
The pan-Thessaly farmers' coordinating committee announced
Wednesday that farmers would begin protest action on January 28,
gradually escalating until February 4 when they would resume the
road and rail blockades which caused widespread disruption
nationwide in December. The 25-day blockade cost the country 1.6
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The farmers suspended their action during the Christmas and New
Year holidays but vowed to repeat it if demands were not met.
</P>
<P>
These demands include lower fuel costs and lower value added
tax (VAT) on farm equipment, higher price supports, especially for
cotton, and a 1.3 billion U.S. dollar rescheduling of debts to the
state Agricultural Bank.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, farmers in central Greece will launch on
January 28 a series of protests, mostly disrupting public
services, to warn the government they mean business ahead of a
full-scale blockade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
