<HEADLINE> EU to Assist Tanzania, Kenya in Building 5 Roads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
plans to spend another 210 billion Tanzania Shillings (about 350
million U.S. Dollars) on five road construction projects in
Tanzania and Kenya in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
EU Head of delegation here Peter Beck Christiansen today told
Presidents Benjamin Mkapa of Tanzania and Daniel Arap Moi of
Kenya that out of the total amount, 150 billion Tanzanian
Shillings would be spend on rehabilitating three roads in the
country and 60 billion Tanzanian Shillings would finance road
rehabilitations in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The official Daily News quoted Christiansen as saying at the
opening ceremony of the Musoma-Isebania road at Sirari border
town between the two sister countries that the roads to be built
in Kenya include Mai-Mahiu-Naivasha-Lanet (110 kilometers) and
Sultan Hamud Mtito-Andei section of Mombasa (135 kilometers).
</P>
<P>
He said on the Tanzania side three roads would undergo heavy
rehabilitations in the next two years. They are the
Mwanza-Nyanguge-Musoma road and urban roads in Mwanza.
</P>
<P>
Others included a road linking Mwanza region with Nzaga and
one from Mwanza to Isaka and Dodoma-Singida road, he added.
</P>
<P>
The EU official appealed to the two governments to ensure that
maintenance of the roads would be given a top priority and
suggested that the two east African States set aside sufficient
budgets for maintenance purposes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the EU head of delegation also advised the two
governments to implement an effective and viable maintenance
system through increased use of the private sector and to enforce
axle load standard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
