<HEADLINE> Liberia's Ruling Council Meets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Liberia's ruling Council of
State has held its first full meeting since October last year
under the good offices of Nigeria, a report reaching here said
today.
</P>
<P>
All the six council members, three warlords and three
civilians, met outside Monrovia, capital of Liberia, on Thursday,
following negotiations by Nigerian Foreign Affairs Minister Tom
Ikimi.
</P>
<P>
The council was set up in 1995 as an interim authority, and it
was the first time it met since Charles Taylor, one of the
vice-chairmen and leader of the National Patriotic Front of
Liberia (NPFL), accused George Boley, another vice-chairman and
leader of the Liberia Peace Council (LPC), of masterminding an
assassination on him in the council building on October 31, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Taylor, whose NPFL ignited the Liberian conflict in December
1989, escaped unhurt, but the incident left five of his
bodyguards dead and spread panic in the capital.
</P>
<P>
And Boley has repeatedly denied any involvement in the attack.
</P>
<P>
Since the incident, much of the council's business has been
conducted at members' homes.
</P>
<P>
"I think it will be correct to say that this meeting is indeed
historic," said Ikimi, who heads a delegation of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) in Liberia to evaluate
the on-going disarmament operation.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Taylor described the meeting as "very
successful", because "it was the first time Boley and I met
face-to-face" since the October incident.
</P>
<P>
"I walked over to Boley and shook his hands and we exchanged
greetings," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I think we in this country must begin to put some of the bad
things behind us and continue to move forward to meet the January
31 deadline for the completion of disarmament in preparation for
elections," Taylor said, quoted by the report.
But it didn't give any other details of the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
