<HEADLINE> Biological Cigarette Filter Invented in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- A group of Greek researchers
today unveiled a new biological cigarette filter which they claim
can largely neutralize the harmful substances of cigarette smoke.
</P>
<P>
Details on the filter were announced at a press conference by
Athens University physiology Professor Ioannis Stavridis,
Assistant Professor G. Deliconstantinos and the director of the
Onassion heart surgery center's medical service, Professor S.
Geroulanos.
</P>
<P>
The new filter, according to its creators, provides effective
protection against tar and other cigarette emissions. In addition,
they say the cost of its production is not higher than that of
conventional filters, while preserving the fragrant ingredients of
cigarettes and not changing their taste.
</P>
<P>
The new filter reportedly has the same appearance as
conventional cigarette filters.
</P>
<P>
According to Prof. Stavridis, the basic ingredient of the
biological filter is haemoglobin, which is found in active
charcoal. He said the filter can withhold or neutralize
carcinogens -- such as nitrogen monoxide derivatives -- to a large
degree. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
