<HEADLINE> Mkapa Stresses Building Roads to Enhance Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa today urged building more road networks which he
said is vital for revitalizing East Africa Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot escape the need to build a network of good roads
that will link our countries and facilitate the efficient
movement of people and goods," Mkapa told a ceremony to mark the
completion of the Musoma-Isebanis road which links Tanzania and
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was also attended by Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi and government officials of both countries.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa hoped that the Musoma-Isebania road would contribute to
the building of firm cooperation between Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa also urged the people of Nyanza province in
Kenya and those of Mare region in Tanzania to see this road as an
opportunity for rapid self-development, and as a chance to
increase legal trade across the common border.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa noted that the road would help strengthen transport
around Lake Victoria zone, adding that it provides an alternative
route to the landlocked countries of Rwanda, Burundi, Uganda and
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"This road is clearly not useful to the people of Kenya and
Tanzania only, but also to those of the entire Great Lakes
region," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has provided an investment of 40 billion
Tanzania Shillings (about 67 million U.S. Dollars) for the
construction of the road.
</P>
<P>
It has pledged to give another 109.5 billion Tanzanian
Shillings (about 182.5 million US Dollars) during the next five
years to rehabilitate 414 km of roads between Dodoma and Mwanza,
and 300 km of rural roads in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The EU has also agreed to finance emergency repairs of the
350-km Isaka-Rusumo Highway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
