<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Sustains Huge Loss to Poor Animal Skin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Africa is sustaining an annual
loss of about 850 million U.S. Dollars as a result of poor
collection of animal hides and skins.
</P>
<P>
A report from the News Agency of Nigeria said today that
livestock owners in Africa hardly receive any added value for a
good quality skin from an animal sold alive.
</P>
<P>
Though sub-Saharan Africa has approximately 10 percent of the
global cattle and buffalo population, the same percentage of
sheep and more than 20 percent of world's goats, its contribution
to global production of skins is less than the equivalent share
of total livestock.
</P>
<P>
Cattle and buffalo hides produced in sub-Saharan Africa is
less than nine percent, whereas Europe, with only eight percent
of cattle population, produces 15 percent of commercial skins,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
This is because of a higher slaughter level and the off-take
of livestocks in developed countries, as well as the fact that
the skins are not collected in sub-Saharan Africa for the market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
