<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Loses Magazine Case to US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Canada has lost a cultural
battle to the United States after an international trade panel
ruled that its efforts to boost the domestic magazine industry
violate world trade rules.
</P>
<P>
A World Trade Organization (WTO) panel has ruled in favor of
the U.S. in its trade dispute with Canada over the "split-run"
edition of the Sports Illustrated magazine, said reports today.
</P>
<P>
The WTO preliminary decision was provided in confidence to the
Canadian and U.S. governments Thursday. The final ruling will be
rendered next month and made public soon after that.
</P>
<P>
Although the Canadian government is widely expected to appeal,
the chance of any major change in the final ruling is quite
remote, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
"No matter what the results, we plan to pursue our cultural
objectives," Nicole Bourget, a spokeswoman for International Trade
Minister Art Eggleton, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Canada is going to continue to promote its cultural objectives
so that Canadians can have access to Canadian publications," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The trade case was filed by the U.S. at the WTO in March 1996
after a long battle over the attempts of the U.S. Time Warner Inc.
to establish an edition of Sports Illustrated in Canada.
</P>
<P>
Sports Illustrated was forced to shut down its three-year-old
Canadian edition after Canada began to impose the 80 percent tax
in December 1995 on the revenue of split-run magazines.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. complained that the new tax violates "national
treatment" provisions in the 1995 WTO pact.
</P>
<P>
Under the WTO, a government must treat foreign companies the
same way they treat domestic ones.
</P>
<P>
Canada insisted that the tax was acceptable because of a WTO
clause that it did not sign, and was a reasonable response to a
U.S. attempt to raid the limited Canadian advertising market.
</P>
<P>
The WTO ruling has dealt a serious blow to the Canadian
government's efforts to protect the cultural sector from
Americanization, the reports noted.
</P>
<P>
At present, half the English-language magazines in Canada and
four-fifths of those sold in newsstands are from abroad, the
reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
