<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Privatization Will Go on: Chiluba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- President Frederick Chiluba
today outlined his new government programs for the next five
years, saying privatization of parastatal companies will continue
to be a key component of the government economic policies.
</P>
<P>
Opening the first session of the new National Assembly,
Chiluba reaffirmed that his government formed early last month is
''irrevocably committed to the privatization program."
</P>
<P>
"It is our intention to complete the privatization program
within our second term of office including the sale of the Zambia
Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM), Mamba collieries, nitrogen
chemicals and Zamtel,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
The second term of the ruling Movement for Multi-Party
Democracy (MMD) government should be a period of delivery and
discipline and most importantly, commitment to duty, and hard
work must become a driving force, said Chiluba, who won his
re-election last November.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said cooperation between the police and the public is
important in preventing crime and arresting criminals. creation
of the neighborhood watch associations has increased community
participation in the fight against crime, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
On education, he said by 1995 education spending had accounted
for almost 14 percent of the total public expenditure and the
government's ultimate target is to commit a higher percentage of
the total budget to education.
</P>
<P>
In the speech, Chiluba also referred to the government
policies on housing, agriculture, social safety network and
environment protection among others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
