<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Trade Union Explains Stand at WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African
Trade Union Unity (OATUU) is opposed to the inclusion of labor
issues in the World Trade Organization (WTO) charter as it would
place developing countries at disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
It would lead to the abuse of the "social clause" in WTO by
the powerful trading countries against the weaker ones, OATUU
Secretary-General Hassan Sunmonu was quoted by a report as saying
in Accra, Ghana on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"It would also block the chances of "the developing country to
resort to cross-retaliation within the WTO dispute settlement
mechanism even when it wins in a complaint against a more
powerful trading country," said Sunmonu.
</P>
<P>
According to the union leader, the "social clause" is an
embodiment of international conventions stipulating core labor
standards like the convention against child labor and the
convention for equal pay for equal work.
</P>
<P>
He maintained that the International Labor Organization (ILO)
is currently the best body to handle labor issues because by its
representation, there is equal opportunity for members to take
collective decisions based on consensus.
</P>
<P>
"International labor standards are set by the tripartite
members of the ILO, namely, governments, employers and workers,
whereas within the WTO only governments are members," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that before the WTO takes on labor issues, it must be
structurally re-organized to give equal opportunities to member
countries, irrespective of their economic status.
</P>
<P>
And even the implementation of the Uruguay Round trade
agreement, which gave birth to WTO, revealed "great inequalities
in the distribution of benefits and costs", said the OATUU
Secretary-General. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
