<HEADLINE> Canadian Minister to Visit Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Foreign Affairs
Minister Lloyd Axworthy will visit Cuba on January 21 and 22 to
discuss a number of bilateral and multilateral issues.
</P>
<P>
"I welcome this opportunity to review our relations and
exchange views on a broad range of issues," Axworthy said today in
a statement announcing the visit.
</P>
<P>
Canada has maintained a long-standing dialogue with Cuba that
includes questions of human rights, good governance, trade and
economic and legal reform, he said.
</P>
<P>
"While Canada and Cuba may not agree on all issues, we have
chosen to discuss our differences of views in a context of
engagement and dialogue, and not one of confrontation and
isolation," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Canada believes it is important to raise and discuss these
views at an appropriate political level," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1945, Canada has pursued its policy of dialogue with Cuba
through successive governments and has maintained interrupted
diplomatic relations with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy's forthcoming visit is the first by a Canadian foreign
minister since 1959, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Secretary of State (Latin America and Africa)
Christine Stewart will go to Cuba along with the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
This visit follows one to Canada by Carlos Lage Davila, the
vice president of the Cuban Council State, in October 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
