<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from Middle East Countries:
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Foreign arms manufacturers are invited to join a
4.5-billion-U.S.-dollar project of upgrading the world's fourth
largest tank fleet in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, Turkey will produce 800 main battle tanks of
the third generation for its armed forces to meet the next
century's defense needs, local newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Turkish military sources as saying that these
tanks would have higher maneuver ability, higher firing power as
well as lower weight.
</P>
<P>
Four Turkish companies would be invited to bid for the project,
but any bidding Turkish company is required to find a foreign
partner which has experience in tank production, according to the
planned tender
</P>
<P>
The project is likely to kick off at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The Central Bank of Cyprus has imposed lower
interests rates on commercial banks, which is regarded as a step
toward total liberalization of the credit system on the island.
</P>
<P>
According to an announcement by the bank, as from today its
lending rate to commercial banks is 7 percent instead of 7.5
percent and the overnight deposits rate 4 percent instead of 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
The bank said its move was dictated by market condition and the
liquidity situation and due to prospects of the island's economy.
</P>
<P>
It added that this should affect interest rates in general and
at a later stage, the rates in dealings between commercial banks
and the private sector. However, in the long run, repercussion
will be in favor of the public, the Bank believed.
</P>
<P>
The cut of the interest rates is considered to be a step toward
total liberalization of the credit system in Cyprus in view of its
prospective accession to the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus applied for European Union full membership in 1990. The
EU is expected to start accession talks with Cyprus toward end of
this year or early next year.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT-- Lebanon has slashed interest rates by 6 percent to
encourage private sector borrowing, Lebanon's Daily Star newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted bankers as saying that the move reflects
increased confidence in the economy.
</P>
<P>
The Bank's Association announced Thursday that it had cut the
prime lending rate, the lowest rate of bank's lending, from 24
percent to 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Kuwait, Lebanon and Egypt will cross-list shares on
each other's exchanges next week, according to the latest issue of
the local economic weekly Middle East News.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Kuwait signed an accord last April to cross-list
shares and Lebanon joined in September.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Lebanon have no restrictions on foreigners trading
shares of national firms. However, Kuwait allows listing of shares
of foreign companies subject to rules set by a market committee.
</P>
<P>
The accord allows Arab residents in Kuwait to invest their
money in Egyptian and Lebanese shares.
</P>
<P>
Dealers were quoted as saying that the new investment channels
are expected to result in a slight decline in trade of Kuwaiti
shares.  
</P>
</TEXT>
