<HEADLINE> China's First Private Museum Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China's first privately owned
museum opened for business today in the country's capital Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Ma Weidu, the 42-year-old owner of Guanfu Classic Art Museum,
has collected more than 1,000 cultural relics since the beginning
of 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Ma man was an editor in a Chinese publishing house, and then
became involved in the movie-making business with bestseller
writer Wang Suo.
</P>
<P>
"It is a symbol of social advancement and stability for the
Chinese government to allow individuals to set up a private
museum," he said.
</P>
<P>
China has permitted some qualified places to establish museums
run by individuals. There have been four such museums registered
in Beijing in the past few years, according to sources at the
Beijing Cultural Relics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The museum with a floor space of 400 square meters is sited in
Liulichang Street, a street full of ancient cultural products in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
An exhibition of porcelain from the Ming and Qing dynasties was
held in the Museum today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
