<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cairo Explosions Blamed on Gas Leakage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 18 (Xinhua) -- A gas leakage could have been the
cause of the fire that sparked the explosions of about 100 gas
cylinders this morning at a gas cylinder storehouse west of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
There are reports of slight injuries and suffocations due to
the fire.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's MENA news agency quoted Director of the Civil Defense
and Fire Department Major General Mahmoud Khalil as saying that
some 150 gas cylinders were saved from fire and are now being
examined as a safety precaution.
</P>
<P>
Six fire engines and 50 firefighters rushed to the scene and
have managed to control the fire that broke out at the gas
cylinder depot in the highly-populated al-Moatamadia, Imbaba
district of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Governor of Giza Abdel Rehim Shehata who was present at the
scene blamed the fire on gas leakage from one of the cylinders.
</P>
<P>
He told MENA that he has ordered immediate check-up of safety
conditions at all gas cylinder storehouses in the governorate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
