<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Newspaper Raps Japanese Ex-Minister for Defending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The DPRK's Rodong Sinmun
today asked Takami Eto, a member of the Japanese House of
Representatives, to openly apologize for his recent statement
whitewashing Japan's 1910-1945 colonial rule of the Korean
Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
In a commentary published today, Rodong Sinmun said that Eto's
statement showed clearly that some Japanese have not changed their
pro-militarism mentality at all. Eto was ousted from the cabinet
in 1995 after making statements distorting history,
</P>
<P>
Pro-militarism activities went rampant in Japan; Eto and his
like are occupying leading positions in the Japanese power
hierarchy and society, thus wielding strong influence in the
political, economic and military fields, said the commentary.
</P>
<P>
It warned that those who spared no time to deny Japan's
aggression history aimed to deceive the Japanese people and lead
Japan on the road of aggression.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Eto reportedly said the treaty that effectively put
the Korean Peninsula under Japanese rule was a "country-to-country
treaty" which can hardly be called invasion.
</P>
<P>
He also said he doubted the credibility of the claim of korean
"comfort women," who were forced into sexual slavery by the
Japanese army during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Eto's comments triggered widespread condemnation on the Korean
Peninsula. 
</P>
</TEXT>
