<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Cairo International Book Fair Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The two-week 29th Cairo
International Book Fair opened today with a rich display of books
which will provide a rich feast to the mind and eye of Egyptians
who are observing their Muslim fasting month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
After kicking off the event, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
lingered around the Fair ground in the Nasser City here, where about
2,400 publishers from 79 countries have put up 3.6 million books
in 27 pavilions.
</P>
<P>
As Mubarak browsed through the Chinese pavilion where nearly
2,000 newly-published books from 26 publishers are on display, the
Chinese-language "A biography on Mubarak" caught his eye.
</P>
<P>
Among the wealth of books neatly laid out on shelves, the
Arabic versions of some Chinese literary classics and reference
books, such as the Arabic-Chinese dictionaries, have attracted
large crowds.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the bountiful varieties of intellectual fodder, an
amitious program of seminars held on the sidelines adds more
flavors to the annual fair, which runs throughout the end of this
month.
</P>
<P>
Prominent Arab folk artists will also grace the annual Cairo
International Book Fair, which was originated in the demand for
provision of proper culture at affordable costs for the majority
of low-income Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, the book fair will have a glimpse of the
cultural and folk art from seven Arab countries, namely, Oman,
Kuwait, Syria, Libya, Morocco, Tunisia and Palestine, at a series
of special soirees given by these participants.
</P>
<P>
It could well become a rare meeting place for a stellar cluster
of great Arab poets who will have their solo soirees to recite
their new poems and discuss cultural issues with readers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, over 100 young talents from remote provinces are
waiting with baited breath for the chance to recite their works at
mass soirees.
</P>
<P>
Artistic elements apart, Cairo originated the book fair 29 year
ago out of a pragmatic need to present local people with the
latest Egyptian and foreign books, encyclopedias, dictionaries and
reference books at moderate prices.
</P>
<P>
Over the years, the fair has grown into the second largest and
most important in the world, with many publishing houses competing
to get a pavilion at the two-week cultural event.
</P>
<P>
To guarantee this year's fair a success, the Egyptian General
Book Organization, the organizing authority, has formed a higher
organizing committee to shape the outlines of the cultural program.
</P>
<P>
During a recent meeting, the committee said the majority of
seminars and discussions will be centered on future prospects of
Egypt, the Arab world and the international arena on the threshold
of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
To add a more cultural aroma to the event, 41 short,
documentary and cartoon films will be aired by the National Cinema
Center to give visitors a rare chance to appreciate the
development of the special genre of the Egyptian cinema.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the organization Samir Sarhan said the fair, which
for the first time coincides with Ramadan, will be open from 11
a.m. to 3 p.m. and from 8 p.m. to midnight. Cultural and poetic
activities will be held during the four-hour evening
session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0055 </DOCNO>
