<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice Premier Urges Better Commodity Circulation Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Li Lanqing today
called for government regulations on commodity markets to be
stepped up and improved to enhance prosperity in the markets.
</P>
<P>
Governments at various levels should work hard to diversify the
pattern of modern circulation institutions, and make structural
readjustments, Li said at a national working conference on
commodity circulation which ended in this capital of Fujian
Province today.
</P>
<P>
Commodity circulation has a major role in the national economy
as China shifts its economic structure from a planned economy into
a market economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is essential to push forward reform of circulation systems
and improve state management of major commodities, he said.
</P>
<P>
Local governments should make efforts to help develop chain
stores, agency sales and second-hand goods markets, the vice
premier said, adding that such businesses should increase their
scales and improve management performance.
</P>
<P>
As current businesses of commodity distribution are generally
small in size and poor in efficiency, reform measures should be
implemented to help them merge into larger operations, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also emphasized the importance of making a success in state
purchase of grain by the grain circulation sector, and reiterated
the no-IOUs policy to farmers. The government wants to stamp out
the practice of issuing I-owe-you notes to farmers during
grain-purchasing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
