<HEADLINE> New Power Plant to Ease Fujian Electricity Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Work on the first phase of the
Huaxia Songyu Power Plant in China, costing three billion yuan
(about 361 million US dollars), has been completed in Xiamen,
Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
No.2 generating unit of the first phase, with a capacity of
300,000 kw, went on line today, after more than four years of
construction.
</P>
<P>
No.1 unit, which went into operation last year, has already
produced 1.3 billion kilowatt hours of electricity.
</P>
<P>
The two coal-fired generating units, located in a
Taiwan-funded invested development zone in the port city of Xiamen,
will be able to produce three billion kilowatt hours of
electricity annually.
</P>
<P>
The two units will greatly ease power shortages in east China's
Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
A key state project, the Huaxia Songyu Power Plant which
belongs to the Xiamen Huaxia International Power Development
Company, is designed to have a total generating capacity of 1.2
million kilowatts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
