<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Calls for Talks to End Peruvian Hostage Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Japan has urged prompt
negotiations between the Peruvian government and hostage-taking
rebels to end the month-old crisis at the Japanese ambassador's
residence in Lima, Kyodo News reported today.
</P>
<P>
"The Japanese government expects a framework for negotiations,
including the composition of the proposed guarantor commission, to
be forged at an early date, and progress to be made toward a
peaceful resolution to the crisis," Kyodo quoted a high-ranking
official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The official was referring to a much-sought resumption of
direct talks between the Peruvian government and Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary Movement (MRTA) rebels holding 73 hostages at the
diplomatic compound.
</P>
<P>
Canada's ambassador to Peru, a former hostage, had agreed to
sit on a guarantor commission overseeing the proposed talks.
</P>
<P>
According to news reports, the Peruvian government said Friday
that it was ready to resume face-to-face talks with the rebels,
but the rebels rejected the government proposal.
</P>
<P>
Almost immediately after the Peruvian government announced the
statement, the MRTA guerrillas set free one captive, the first in
17 days.
</P>
<P>
The hostage drama began on December 17 when a group of MRTA
guerrillas stormed the Japanese ambassador's residence and took
hostage hundreds of diplomats and dignitaries inside, who were
attending a reception marking Japanese Emperor Akihito's birthday.
</P>
<P>
The rebels are demanding the Peruvian government to free
hundreds of their detained comrades in exchange of the release of
the remaining hostages at the Japanese ambassador's residence.
</P>
<P>
The rebels set free most of the captives in several batches,
but still kept 73 in their hands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0069 </DOCNO>
