<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israelis, Palestinians Demonstrate Against Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Several hundred Israeli
peace activists and Palestinian villagers today launched a
demonstration in the West Bank village of Hirbata, near
Ramallah, against land confiscation by Israeli settlers.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators marched from the village to a plot of land,
one and half kilometers away, which is being threatened by the
encroachments of the Kiryat Sefer settlers. Olive seedlings were
planted there by Israelis and Palestinians together.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Gush Shalom, the Israeli Peace Bloc, said
that the struggle for a Hebron deal is hardly concluded and
already the bigger struggle has started, the struggle for the
future of the West Bank, which will decided the real chances for
peace.
</P>
<P>
"The Netanyahu Government had put off signature of the Hebron
Agreement for as long as it could. In the agreement itself it
had put off completion of the further redeployment on the West
Bank for a further 19 months. Clearly, the government tries to
buy time," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said, "In the past weeks, a struggle for the
land, constituting a virtual mini-war, has broken out all over
the West Bank. Everywhere the settlers, backed by the army, try
to take over any available piece of land, using the most
impossible legal tricks, and the most flimsy excuses. Bulldozers
are deployed, fenses are erected for the 'extension' of existing
settlements, which sometimes amounts to the de-facto creation of
new ones." "Land grabbing affects not only the so-called 'state
lands' (some of which have been in the hands of Palestinian
villagers for generations) but also lands whose private
ownership by Palestinians is unquestioned," it added.
</P>
<P>
"The new agreement gives the government 19 months until
redeployment is completed in most of the West Bank. Clearly,
each and every one of these days will be used for land-grabbing,
with the aim of creating a situation in which a Palestinian
state will be impossible -- which would make peace impossible,
as well," the statement concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
