<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Build Shanghai into International Economic Centre: Qiao Shi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Qiao Shi, a senior Chinese
leader has called for the nation's economic powerhouse, Shanghai,
to speed up its drive to become an international economic,
financial and trade center.
</P>
<P>
Qiao, member of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau
of the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee, made the call
during a week-long inspection trip to Shanghai that ended on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"As long as Shanghai seizes the opportunities and brings its
own advantages into full play, the city will definitely be built
into such a center," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qiao, also chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress, China's top legislature, said Shanghai has a
significant role to play in China's economic development and
opening to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
With a good base and favourable conditions already in place,
the city will be able to achieve great progress in many fields,
including modern industry, science and technology, finance and
foreign trade, he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that in order to score a faster economic growth, it
is essential for Shanghai to accelerate the development and
opening-up of the Pudong New Area, which enjoys a number of
preferential policies granted by the central authorities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it will also be conducive to Shanghai's development
to increase economic and technological cooperation with China's
central and western regions, he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged local officials to continue to deepen reform, open the
city wider to the outside world, and solve practical problems, to
make greater contribution to the nation's prosperity.
</P>
<P>
The leader also stressed the importance of building new
facilities to improve local residents' cultural lives and develop
popular culture and arts.
</P>
<P>
During the trip, Qiao visited the Pudong New Area, the Baoshan
Steel and Iron Company and a number of other places, and held a
meeting on state-owned enterprises with local officials and
managers.
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of Shanghai's reform of state-owned
enterprises, and expected the reforms to be carried out even
further with boldness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
