<HEADLINE> Relief Ordered for Victims of Blast in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani authorities
have issued directives on relief and rescue operations for victims
of a bomb blast in Lahore earlier this afternoon, the official
Associated Press of Pakistan reported.
</P>
<P>
Pervez Masud, chief secretary of Pakistan's Punjab Province,
issued the directives while visiting the site of the blast, which
killed 12 people and injured about 30, at the District and
Sessions Court of Lahore, capital of Punjab Province.
</P>
<P>
The chief secretary also visited the injured at hospitals.
</P>
<P>
He ordered local health officials to provide best treatment
possible for the victims.
</P>
<P>
A leader of Sapah-e-Sahaba Pakistan, a local religious militant
group, was among the killed and another leader of the group was
critically injured.
</P>
<P>
Two local journalists were also killed in the incident while
two judges were injured.
</P>
<P>
Tehrik Jafria Pakistan (TJP), a political party to contest the
forthcoming general elections scheduled for February 3, condemned
the blast.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the TJP said the explosion was a
pre-planned terrorist act aiming to further deteriorate the law
and order situation and fan sectarianism in the country.
</P>
<P>
The governing body of the Lahore Press Club has expressed deep
grief over the tragic death of the two journalists.
</P>
<P>
It called upon the government to take stringent measures to
protect the life of the people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
