<HEADLINE> Changping Becomes Railway Hub in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 18 (Xinhua) -- A small town in southern
China's Guangdong Province has become a train spotter's paradise
from today.
</P>
<P>
An extra 22 more inter-city rail services will be stopping
each day in Changping, a small town in Dongguan City in Guangdong
every day.
</P>
<P>
Changping is the crossing point for three major rail lines
running through Guangdong Province, including the Beijing-Kowloon,
the Guangzhou-Meizhou-Shantou, and the Guangzhou-Shenzhen railways.
</P>
<P>
The town is also the only other transfer station for trains
from inland cities to Hong Kong, besides the Shenzhen railway
station.
</P>
<P>
The town has three railway stations. The north station only
deals in freight transportation, with the south station used for
passenger trains, and the newly-completed east station handling
both freight and passenger trains.
</P>
<P>
At least 70 trains stop at the south station everyday, carrying
up to 10,000 passengers daily.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
