<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COSCO to Contribute to HK's Shipping Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China Ocean Shipping (Group)
Co. (COSCO) will contribute to maintaining Hong Kong's role as an
international shipping center, Chen Zhongbiao, president of COSCO,
 said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony to mark the maiden voyage of a large container
vessel, "Lu He," here today, Chen said that after Hong Kong
returns to its motherland on July 1, 1997, the status of Hong Kong
 in the international shipping industry will be kept and if there
is any change, it will be for the better.
</P>
<P>
Chen, also chairman of the China Shipowners' Association, said
that COSCO will continue to develop its business in Hong Kong so
as to make its contribution to the sustained prosperity and
further development of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He said no ports in the Chinese mainland can replace Hong Kong
as a shipping cargo transit center in quite a long time.
</P>
<P>
He described "Lu He" as a symbol of COSCO's commitment. The
vessel is the first of six 5,250-TEU (twenty-foot equivalent
units) ships ordered by COSCO from Kawasaki Heavy Industries
Ltd. of Japan.
</P>
<P>
The ship was delivered to COSCO on January 8 this year. After
her maiden call to Hong Kong "Lu He" will continue on her maiden
voyage, culminating in calls to ports on the West Coast of the
United States before returning to Asia.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen, following "Lu He," COSCO will put five other
 5,250-TEU vessels and seven 3,400-TEU vessels into service, which
 will bring COSCO's container carrying capacity up to 250,000 TEUs
 from its current 184,000 TEUs.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that COSCO will accelerate its fleet expansion,
improve management and provide high-quality service to its
customers all over the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
