<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Hold Labor Conferences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Two major international
conferences focusing on labor issues, especially the employment
crisis in Africa, are scheduled to be held in South Africa this
month, said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
These include the fifth biennial meeting of African Employment
Planners in Pretoria from January 20 to 24 and the seventh
high-level Pan African Employers' Conference in Johannesburg from
January 29 to 31, both under the auspices of the International
Labor Organization, the source added.
</P>
<P>
The African Employment Planners meeting is aimed to review the
overall employment crisis in Africa and find possible solutions
for unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-eight African governments, 12 workers's organizations
and 12 employers' organizations are expected to attend the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Participants will also discuss elements of the
recently-launched "Jobs for Africa" program, which is run jointly
by the ILO and United Nations Development Program (UNDP) in an
attempt to address the ever-increasing poverty in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Pan African Employers' Conference, hosted by
Business Africa, is scheduled to focus on issues such as South
Africa's place in African trade and cooperation, and the role of
employer organizations in promoting sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
The conference will bring together representatives of
employers' organizations from all over Africa to deliberate on
economic liberalization and its social impact in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
