<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Maize Production Yields Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Johannesburg, January 18 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's maize crop
would yield about nine million tons this season, the National Maize
Producers Organisation said today.
</P>
<P>
The organisation's General Manager Kit Clus said plantings of white
maize in South Africa were about 12.5 percent down on last year while
plantings of yellow maize were about 1.5 percent up.
</P>
<P>
The overall crop would be about seven percent smaller than last
season's, he said.
</P>
<P>
Reasons behind the smaller area under maize included
uncertainty over prices and the abolition of the price subsidy.
</P>
<P>
Maize crops were generally in good condition in South Africa, but
parts of the country's central areas were dry in the past season.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is the biggest maize producer and exporter in the
African continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Retain Dual Exchange Rate in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will retain its dual exchange
rate in 1997, Head of State General Sani Abacha announced in his
budget speech this morning.
</P>
<P>
The announcement is contrary to widespread speculations that the
country's controversial dual exchange rate will be merged this year at
around 50 Naira to one Dollar.
</P>
<P>
The head of state said that the official exchange rate will remain
22 Naira to one dollar, and the Autonomous Foreign Exchange Market
rate will also remain 80 Naira to one Dollar.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the government's policy has generated a stability of
the Naira in the foreign exchange market and it is necessary to ensure
that the exchange regime is maintained at a sustainable level.
</P>
<P>
His speech implies that the government also wishes that the
policy will serve as a potent weapon to contain inflation, which
according to him, had declined from 72.8 percent in 1995 to 28
percent in 1996, but still eight points above the 20 percent
government target.
</P>
<P>
However, Abacha indicated that the country's two foreign exchange
rates will be ultimately merged.
</P>
<P>
"Government will therefore continue its policy of guided
deregulation, and in repect of the exchange rate regime, government
would maintain the current system with the ultimate aim of a
subsequent merger," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
