<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Volcano Spewing Fewer Hot Fumes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Less spewing of hot fumes was
seen from Indonesia's volcano Merapi, which erupted Friday, but
alert is still on for the volcano's re-eruption, the Antara News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
About 8,000 people were evacuated Friday as Indonesia's most
active volcano erupted, gushing molten lava and spewing clouds of
hot ash over vast areas.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Yogyakarta Office of the Merapi Surveillance
Section, Mas Atje Purbawinana, said today that in the 12 hours to
6:00 a.m. Saturday (2300 Friday GMT), the volcano spewed hot fumes
twice toward the Krasak River, Boyong, Bebeng and the Sat River.
Earlier on Friday, it spat out fumes 17 times.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the volcano sent out red-hot lava 36 times
toward the same places, the report said.
</P>
<P>
There was no official report on casualties but unconfirmed
reports said six people went missing Friday.
</P>
<P>
The last eruption of the 2,968-meter-high Merapi volcano was on
November 22, 1994, killing more than 60 people, injuring dozens
and destroying properties.
</P>
<P>
Merapi, one of the 127 volcanoes in Indonesia, is classified as
one of the most active in the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
