<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Government Releases 1997 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LAGOS, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Sani Abacha this morning announced the government's 1997 budget#,
which projects a total expenditure of 247 billion Naira (about 3
billion Dollars), 41 percent up from last year.
</P>
<P>
The budget expects a total revenue of 404 billion Naira
(above five billion Dollars) for the government, 60 percent
of which will come from the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
The revenue projection is said to be a conservative one, as
it foresees an oil price of 17 Dollars per barrel, whereas the
selling price was 20 Dollars last week.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to widespread speculations, Abacha announced that
the dual exchange rate will be retained in 1997, with the offcial
rate remaining 22 Naira to one Dollar and the Autonomous Foreign
Exchange rate 80 Naira to one Dollar.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Nigeria's foreign debt has dropped from
32.6 billion Dollars at the end of 1995 to 28.1 billion Dollars
at present, thanks to "effective debt management".
</P>
<P>
He expressed the wish to speed up the negotiations with the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank on Nigeria's
Medium Term Economic Strategy so that the country can benefit
from the Paris Club's debt relief program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
