<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Signs Up 250,000 Walkie-Talkie Clients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen, China's first special
economic zone, had signed up more than 250,000 mobile phone users
by the end of 1996, ranking fourth among cities in the country's
walkie-talkie stakes.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the per capita mobile phone density rate, the
Shenzhen people are China's number one buyers, said the journal
"Communication Weekly."
</P>
<P>
Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou, capital of Guangdong Province,
each have more than 300,000 mobile phones customers, and hold the
top three in the consumer list.
</P>
<P>
But the growth in momentum of the special zone is more
formidable. In last year alone, the city signed up more than
100,000 mobile phone users, which even exceeded the rise in
ordinary telephone subscribers.
</P>
<P>
This year the special zone's mobile telecom bureau will expand
its mobile phone switching capacity by 250,000 lines. And the
city's mobile phone users will have an automatic roaming service
to enable calls to be made between Shenzhen and Macao, Singapore
and Spain by the end of this June.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
