<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bull Market Draws Listing Hopefuls in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of Hong
Kong has received nearly 30 applications for new listings so far
this year as companies seek to cash in on the market's bull run,
South China Morning Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Chief Executive Herbert Hui Ho-ming said the listing
division is processing nearly 30 A-1 forms, the first step toward
a formal application for a listing.
</P>
<P>
"The large number of applications may be related to the fact
that it is the beginning of the year and the market is on a bull
run," he noted.
</P>
<P>
In the next 40 days, five teams at the listing division will
study each case to see if they are qualified for a listing, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Listings in the territory have been rising steadily, with 49
companies coming to the market in 1996 compared with 26 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong stocks edged even higher yesterday, marking the third
consecutive record high close. The Hang Seng Index, the barometer
of the market, rose 25.72 points to finish at 13,856.  
</P>
</TEXT>
