<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Social Development Enjoys Steady Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China's overall social
development has witnessed an annual rate of nine percent during
the 1990's, the State Statistics Bureau has reported.
</P>
<P>
And the rate is expected to be ten percent during the 1996-2000
period, the bureau predicted in a report.
</P>
<P>
China's social development index comprises of ten areas, the
environment, population, economic strength, income distribution,
labor and employment, social security, medicine and health care,
education and science and technology, culture and sports as well
as public security.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the overall social development of China's
eastern and coastal regions have led the country, but the rest
part of China has quickened the pace of their social development.
</P>
<P>
"The central and western parts of China have enjoyed a speed in
social development above the national average since 1991," said
the report.
</P>
<P>
The report also pointed out that many evident problems are to
be tackled in China. It also listed money-losing state-owned
enterprises, the difficulties in controlling the moving of farmers
into cities, a widening gap in incomes, and environment pollution as
examples of problems to be solved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
