<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Port Opens to Foreign Vessels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- A Panama-registered tanker
carrying liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) sailed into Taicang Port's
petrochemical berth in east China's Jiangsu Province today.
</P>
<P>
The event inaugurated the opening of Taicang Port to ships and
vessels flying foreign flags.
</P>
<P>
Situated on the southern bank of the Yangtze River estuary,
Taicang Port has a 38 kilometer long wharf line and is capable of
handling ships of 50,000 dead weight tonnages (DWT).
</P>
<P>
While on a visit to Shanghai last November, Chinese Premier Li
Peng called for an accelerated expansion of ports on the lower
reaches of the Yangtze River, citing Taicang Port in particular,
by building the port into an important part of Shanghai's
international shipping hub.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, four major zones will be built at
the port, an international town funded by the China Ocean
Shipping Group Corporation, a petrochemical industrial zone, an
investment zone along the Yangtze River and a comprehensive
development zone.
</P>
<P>
The port has already attracted 250 million U.S. dollars in
domestic and overseas investment, and five investment projects
have been completed.
</P>
<P>
Construction has also started on an international town for
China Ocean Shipping Group Corporation and three container
berths. A ground breaking ceremony was also held for the
construction of premises for Mobil (Taicang) LPG Company, with an
investment of 15.7 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
