<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Bulgaria's opposition party, the Union of Democratic Forces,
has called on the socialist government to make "a declaration on
the salvation of the nation," including the drafting of a new
policy for the central bank, putting the bank under protection,
setting up a government of technicians, and negotiating with the
International Monetary Fund to prevent the country from bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
-- French President Jacques Chirac has called on Hungary not to
forget French enterprises when Budapest signs big contracts with
international businesses. He expressed his regret that France has
so far failed to win any big deal in Hungary, although Paris has
become the third largest investor in the country after Germany and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
-- In Switzerland, the dispute over Jewish properties deposited
in Swiss banks during World War II, and the threat to boycott Swiss
banks by world Jewish organizations have re-awakened the old feeling
of anti-Semitism. The Swiss Federation of Israeli Communities has
been receiving letters expressing hatred of Jews.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- One day after he signed the deal on Hebron with Palestinians,
Israeli Prime Minister Benyamin Netanyahu reaffirmed in an interview
with Le Figaro that Israel will never negotiate the status of
Jerusalem with Palestinians. He also said that his government will
not talk with Syria on Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
-- Seven years after the discovery of the virus of hepatitis C,
one percent of the French population, or half a million people
living in France, could have been infected by the epidemic, which
has become a major problem in the public health of France.  
</P>
</TEXT>
