<HEADLINE> Syrian Vice-President Leaves Cairo for Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Vice President Abdul Halim
Khaddam left here this morning with his accompanying delegation
following the end of a one-day visit to Egypt during which he met
with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
So far, there has been no reports of the scheduled resumption
of talks this morning between Khaddam, Syrian Foreign Minister
Farouq al-Shara, Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri and
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian delegation had held talks with Ganzouri on bilateral
relations and Arab affairs Friday evening before meeting President
Hosni Mubarak on the suspended Israeli-Syrian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
During their two-hour talks, the Syrian vice-president conveyed
a letter to Mubarak from Syrian President Hafez al-Assad, which
dealt with the current situation in the Arab world and the Middle
East peace process, the Egyptian Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A day before the Syrian-Egyptian talks, Syrian President Assad
received a telephone call from Mubarak on some Arab issues of
mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Details were unknown about their conversation, which came a day
after Israel and the Palestinian Authority signed a deal that
secured a partial Israeli troop withdrawal from the West Bank town
of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
However, Syrian official daily Al-Thawra Thursday slammed the
agreement, saying it was the death knell of the Mideast peace
process. "There is nothing new to encourage Syria to resume peace
talks with Israel," it lamented.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the U.S. has ruled out the
possibility of an imminent resumption of talks on the
Israeli-Syrian track. U.S. State Department Spokesman Nicholas
Burns said no breakthrough was achieved on the Syrian track last
year.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian peace talks, which began in 1991, are frozen
over the future of the Golan Heights, captured by Israel in the
1967 Middle East War. Talks broke off in March last year after
four suicide bombings in Israel killed over 60 people.
</P>
<P>
While Syria insisted on the return of the Golan Heights as a
precondition for peace, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu
has said Israel will retain the strategic plateau as it is crucial
to Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, which is the first Arab country to make peace with
Israel, plays a leading role in brokering peace in
Arab-Israeli talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
