<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Shows Marked Trade Surplus over Nine Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's exports reached
nearly 3.1 billion Kuwaiti dinars or 10.23 billion U.S. dollars
in the first nine months of 1996, showing a surplus of about 4.62
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
according to an economic report released Friday by the
Al-shaal weekly, oil exports of the gulf country totaled 2.9
billion dinars to make up 94.5 percent of Kuwait's total exports
of 10.23 billion dollars while imports stood at some 1.7 billion
dinars (5.61 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
If the surplus was computed for a full year it would have
jumped to 1.8 billion dinars (5.94 billion U.S. dollars), the
report added.
</P>
<P>
It attributed the huge surplus to the high oil prices, mainly
during the last quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
The increase of the general average of Kuwaiti crude oil
price was about three dollars per barrel in 1996 compared with
that of 1995. Kuwait exports about 1.5 million barrels of crude
oil a day.
</P>
<P>
The report anticipated a drop of the trade surplus in 1997
due to an expected lower oil price after the end of the cold
season.
</P>
<P>
The oil prices rose to around 16.8 U.S. dollars per barrel in
1995 from 15.5 U.S. dollars in 1994 and again jumped to around
20 U.S. dollars during the last quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Due to the oil price increase, the report said, Kuwaiti gross
domestic product (GDP) might register a five to six percent
increase in 1996 on the basis of 8.2 percent the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The report said "we expected a moderate growth in the GDP of
1996 compared with that of 1995 in current prices."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's budget for 1996-97 fiscal year presented on October
1, 1996 envisaged that the expenditure would be at 4.21 billion
dinars (13.89 billion U.S. dollars) and revenues at 3 billion
dinars (9.9 billion U.S. dollars) with an assumed deficit of
3.96 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
