<HEADLINE> Up to 30 Might Be Killed in Bomb Blast in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Up to 30 people might be
killed and 30 others injured in a bomb blast in Pakistan's eastern
city of Lahore this afternoon, said News Network International, a
local Urdu-language news agency.
</P>
<P>
One religious leader was among the killed in the blast that
took place at the District and Sessions Court of Lahore, capital
of Punjab province, at peak hours in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Maulana Ziaur Rahman of Sapah-e-Sahaba Pakistan (SSP) was
killed and Maulana Azam Tariq Rahim, another SSP leader, was
critically injured.
</P>
<P>
The two SSP leaders, earlier arrested for involvement in
sectarian violence, were produced before the court for grant of
bail when the bomb exploded.
</P>
<P>
Two local journalists were also killed in the incident while
two judges were injured.
</P>
<P>
A large number of litigants injured in the bomb explosion were
taken to local hospitals for medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
The official Associated Press of Pakistan put the death toll at
12.
</P>
<P>
The SSP is an influential militant religious group in the
country that is strongly against Shiite Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said that the high-intensity bomb was remotely
controlled and planted in a motorcycle in the court where a large
number of people were present on the occasion.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that an anti-SSP religious party planted the
bomb to kill the SSP leaders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
