<HEADLINE> HK Safety Belt Law Helps Cut Road Casualties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- A newly-introduced safety
belt law has helped reduce significantly the number of rear-seat
passengers injured in private car accidents, local newspapers
reported today.
</P>
<P>
A study made by the Hong Kong Transport Department showed that
592 rear-seat passengers were injured in traffic accidents in the
first six months since it was made compulsory for rear-seat
passengers to wear safety belts last June.
</P>
<P>
This represented a 17 percent drop from 717 during the same
period in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The department's senior engineer Ying Fun-fong said yesterday
that the new law has made it safer to travel on the road.
</P>
<P>
Private cars registered as of June 1 last year must be fitted
out with rear seat belts.
</P>
<P>
It is also compulsory for rear-seat passenger to wear safety
belts when traveling in cars fitted with rear-seat safety belts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
