<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increase Recorded in Hong Kong Labor Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Average labor earnings,
covering major sectors in Hong Kong and measured by payroll per
person engaged, gained 8.6 percent in nominal terms in the third
quarter of 1996 over a year earlier, figures from the Hong Kong
Census and Statistics Department show.
</P>
<P>
The increase was 3.1 percent in real terms, after discounting
changes in consumer prices.
</P>
<P>
Most of the sectors recorded increases, among which the
wholesale, retail and import/export trades, restaurants and hotels
sector recorded the fastest -- 10.8 percent in nominal terms or
5.2 percent in real terms.
</P>
<P>
The overall wage index covering selected major sectors showed a
relatively less rapid increase than average labor earnings.
</P>
<P>
The index rose by 6.4 percent in nominal terms and by only 1.2
percent in real terms in September 1996 over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The relatively faster increase in earnings as compared with
wages was due to more overtime pay and the issue of irregular
payments in some sectors, which were covered in earnings but not
in wages, the department said, adding that this can be seen as an
indication of intensive manpower utilization in the sectors
concerned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0124 </DOCNO>
