<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin &AMP; rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of the
crude palm oil (CPO), tin and rubber closed the week either firmer
or quiet.
</P>
<P>
The CPO physicals market which was spurred by strong leads on
the palm oil futures market closed the week firmer.
</P>
<P>
January-South surged 17.50 ringgit (about 7 U.S. dollars) this
week to 1,335 ringgit (about 534 U.S. dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
The market was choppy throughout the week, but the bullish end-
December production figures released by the Palm Oil Registration
and Licensing Authority (PORLA) on Wednesday aided the palm oil
cash market.
</P>
<P>
The PORLA reported that December 1996 CPO production dropped 16
percent to 637,865 tons from 762,539 tons.
</P>
<P>
On the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM), the metal also settled
the week higher when a surge on other metals on the London Metal
Exchange (LME) spurred strong local buying interest.
</P>
<P>
On the LME, zinc and nickel made a record high on Thursday
overnight as zinc hit a 23-month high and nickel scored strongest
levels for the year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, a buying spree for three month tin enabled the
KLTM to recoup last week's losses as bids amounted 415 tons
against offers of 78 tons.
</P>
<P>
While trading of the first three days were choppy, profit
taking on the LME on Friday dampened trading which clipped further
gains as the market settled at 14.59 ringgit (about 5.84 U.S.
dollars) per kg at the close this week against 14.37 ringgit
(about 5.75 U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
The week's turnover amounted 582 tons against 456 tons last
week.
</P>
<P>
But the Malaysian rubber market was very quiet this week on
lack of interest as buyers were sidelined.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said buyers were expected to return only after the long
double festival holidays in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
Reports of excess stocks in China and Japan contributed to the
weaker trading this week as buyers would not seek local rubber.
</P>
<P>
The consolidation of the ringgit also contributed to the
sluggish trading this week with local rubber becoming relatively
more expensive than those in neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
However, players were still bullish about the market as they
expect the long holidays to lift the price up.
</P>
<P>
February RSS One stopped at 304.00 sen (about 121.6 U.S. cents)
per kg, down 2.50 sen (about 1 U.S. cent) from 306.50 sen (about
122.6 U.S. cents) last week and SMR 20 at 299.50 sen (about 119.8
U.S. cents), down 4.50 sen (about 1.8 U.S. cents) from 304.00 sen
(about 121.6 U.S. cents) previously.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
