<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) recovered this week from earlier
losses with improved buying interest by both retail and
institutional players ahead of the double Chinese and Muslim New
Year celebrations next month.
</P>
<P>
Trading was dominated by the second board counter and lower
liners on the main board during the week.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting the trend, the all main board share Emas Index rose
0.35 of a point to 349.94 points.
</P>
<P>
Bargain hunting on blue chips towards the end of the week
managed to trim some of Composite Index's earlier losses but it
was still within the red zone. The 100-stock Index was 7.83 points
lower to close at 1,224.55.
</P>
<P>
The Industrial Index slipped 40.99 points to 2,350.81, while
the second board rallied in the last three days of the week to
close 5.92 points higher at 612.93.
</P>
<P>
Before investors started picking the stocks this week, some had
switched to the foreign exchange market for profit to take
advantage of the soaring Ringgit which hit a 17-month high against
the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Ringgit surged passing the 2.46 level to the U.S. dollar on
Monday but closed the week at 2.4822/32 on short covering for the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
Buying interest was pronounced only towards the end of the week
with both retail and institutional investors coming in to support
stocks which had tumbled after its correction.
</P>
<P>
The weekly main board ready turnover increased to 1.012 billion
shares worth 5.742 billion Ringgit (about 2.3 billion U.S.
dollars) from 766.343 million shares valued at 4.443 billion
Ringgit (about 1.78 billion dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover was 242.102 million shares worth
3.005 billion Ringgit (about 1.2 billion dollars) from 327.085
million shares valued at 3.767 billion Ringgit (about 1.51 billion
dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Off market deals amounted to 380.540 million shares worth 2.191
billion Ringgit (about 880 million dollars) from 237.291 million
shares valued at 1.329 billion Ringgit (about 530 million dollars)
previously.  
</P>
</TEXT>
