<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Car imports of Saudi Arabia will see a pick up
during 1997 after a decline which began 1993, market analysts said.
</P>
<P>
According to Saudi daily Arab News, the analysts said Japanese
cars, which lost ground to other manufacturers over the past
years due to the appreciation of the yen, are staging a comeback
with 1997 sales expected to pick up.
</P>
<P>
The improvement is attributed to competitive pricing and
introduction of new models to cater for medium and small
markets. Prices of Japanese cars which were reported to have gone
down in 1996 will see a further cuts.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese lost to the U.S. and Korean manufacturers whose
cars gained ground in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia accounts for 70 percent of car imports in
the six countries of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) which
groups Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Oman, Bahrain
besides Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's national economy will be under control of
foreign capital if no effective measures are taken, State Minister
Sabri Tekir has said.
</P>
<P>
Tekir told the Finance Club based in Istanbul, the largest
city of Turkey, that heavy dependence on foreign capital will
leave the country's economy under control of foreign powers,
according to local newspaper Daily News today.
</P>
<P>
"This situation can not continue forever. If one thirds of
the budget is going to finance interest payments alone, Turkey
can not achieve economical or political stability," Tekir said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that Turkey's domestic debts stood 78 billion
U.S. dollars at the end of last year, and the country had to use
15 billion U.S. dollars to cover interest payments.
</P>
<P>
He called on the government to pay high attention to the
development of the industrial production, employment as well as
exports in a bid to restore people's confidence in the
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Sabanci Holding's
cement division, Akcansa, plans to sell 8.534 million tons of
cement in 1997, a company official said.
</P>
<P>
Akcansa, based in Istanbul, is a joint venture by Sabanci
Holding, the second largest business company of Turkey, and
Belgian Cimenteries CBRSA.
</P>
<P>
According to local newspaper Daily News today, Akcansa
President Ayduk Celenk said "we will use more than 80 percent of
the group's total 10.82-million-ton cement capacity and sell all
of the output."
</P>
<P>
The Sabanci division operates six cement plants in Turkey,
with an annual production of 6 million tons. The Sabanci
Holding has several other cement divisions.
</P>
<P>
Celenk said that Akcansa was considering to build new
plants or to expand its productive capacity on the current
basis.
</P>
<P>
Turkey foresees a good market for cement in 1997, and the
positive tendency is expected to remain unchanged until 2010, he
said.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Canada agreed on establishing a free trade
zone, within the framework of which duties between the two
countries will be reduced gradually and full exemption of duties
will be put into force in 12 years since the start of the
implementation.
</P>
<P>
Canadian exports to Egypt hit 130 billion dollars, yet
Egypt's exports to Canada did not exceed 19 million.
</P>
<P>
Canada has concluded a similar agreement with Israel, which
will be put into force next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investigations to Be Conducted into Alleged Improper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Telecom
Corporation and the Contracts Division of the Finance Ministry
have been instructed to expedite the investigation into alleged
improprieties in the former's deal with a foreign firm.
</P>
<P>
The investigation into an allegation of improprieties in a
tender awarded by Malaysia Telecom Corporation to Swedish
multinational Ericsson Telecommunications has been classified as
an "urgent matter," Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia Telecom and the Contracts Division have been
instructed to expedite the investigation and to submit a report as
soon as possible, Anwar, who is also finance minister, told
reporters after a function here.
</P>
<P>
"I have asked for it to be speeded up. It is not necessary to
take too much time because all the records are still there. I have
classified it as an urgent matter," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government on Wednesday instructed that an investigation be
conducted into the alleged improprieties in the award of a
contract by Malaysia Telecom to Ericsson for the supply of
telecommunications equipment.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, who is now in California on a
visit to the United States, also said yesterday the matter should
be investigated.
</P>
<P>
On whether the preliminary report he received contains
allegations against any cabinet minister or senior officials of
Malaysia Telecom, Anwar said "there were references but there
were no specific allegations. I've not seen the detailed report."
</P>
<P>
However, he said "we should be transparent. If there is any
report, we should take it up. I don't think we should be unduly
concerned but we should be positive and we should take it up
seriously."
</P>
<P>
According to procedures, all tender awards have to be approved
by the Tender Board before final approval was given by the Finance
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore the investigation will cover the question of whether
the procedures were observed, whether there were discrepancies at
any level, be it the Telecom level or Treasury level, whether
there was actually a reference to the Treasury at all," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that all speculations should cease as an investigation
was being conducted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
