<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Sign Information Technology Deal Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will soon sign
the Information Technology Agreement (ITA), a multilateral pact to
liberalize a wide range of information technology products,
Malaysia's official news agency Bernama reported today.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia would be ready to "sign on the dotted line" in July,
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, who is now in
California, was quoted as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir is ending his week-long working visit to the United
States today, a trip aimed at promoting his country's proposed
Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC) which has received positive
responses from the world's renowned high technology companies.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Malaysia didn't sign the agreement in Singapore
last month when it was negotiated during the inaugural ministerial
meeting of the World Trade Organization because it wanted to
review the provisions of the agreement to see if it would have a
harmful effect on Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Malaysian reporters at Santa Clara, California, he
said Malaysia will not impose any duty on the import of multimedia
equipment under the Multimedia Bill of Guarantees to companies
receiving MSC status from the Multimedia Development Corporation
(MDC).
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said his government also planned to review, and if
necessary "amend or formulate new laws" to provide venture capital
for small and medium-sized companies, especially start-up
companies involving multimedia.
</P>
<P>
He called on Silicon Valley companies to invest in the MSC and
"to be our partners in exploring these exciting new frontiers."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir was scheduled to head for Tokyo today to continue his
mission of promoting the MSC to Japanese IT companies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moi Calls for Political Federation in E. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi has said that "a political federation of east Africa should
be made a reality now than ever before", according to an East
African Standard report today.
</P>
<P>
"Such a federation will be realized soon enough", Moi said on
Friday while addressing the commissioning of the
Musoma-Sirari-Isebania- Makuyu road connecting Kenya and
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan leader noted that the political federation will
give more impetus to social and economic growth within the east
African region.
</P>
<P>
Moi reaffirmed that countries should be left alone to manage
their own affairs and must not be dictated upon by foreigners who
do not understand them.
</P>
<P>
It is the duty of Africans to strive and become
self-sustaining instead of waiting for assistance from other
countries which has strings attached nearly always, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that sustainable economic growth and
development for east Africa can best be achieved through
co-operation and integration.
</P>
<P>
It is very important for east African countries to harmonize
their transport and communications network and co-ordination,
President Moi stated, adding that a mechanism is required for
proper co-ordination of an efficient inter-country road network.
</P>
<P>
On the 112-kilometer road funded by the European Union at a
cost of 70 million U.S. Dollars, the president said that the road
network will be a big boost to the east African regional
co-operation in particular and the Great Lakes region in general.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa said
that a political federation can stimulate trade in the region and
thereby increase economic activities.
</P>
<P>
Both President Moi and President Mkapa stressed on the need
for easing of customs and immigration rules to enable local
people transact their businesses with minimal hindrance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Securities Board to Tighten Surveillance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Securities and Exchange
Board of India (SEBI) has taken measures to tighten surveillance
mechanism over stock exchanges all over the country in a bid to
stabilize trading prices at stock markets.
</P>
<P>
The streamlined surveillance will relate to the imposition of
price ranges, making it mandatory for the stock exchanges to
implement price ranges uniformly based on the previous day's
closing price of the stock. At the moment, price ranges on some
exchanges were based on the opening price of stocks on the same
trading day.
</P>
<P>
The new surveillance measures followed a decision taken by the
securities market watchdog at the end of a meeting Thursday with
representatives of all the major stock exchanges. The meeting was
convened to review the volatility on the bourses following the
stock market indices' roller-coaster ride over the last three
days.
</P>
<P>
SEBI has decided to probe the wild price volatility on the stock
exchanges. Data and information regarding price movements and
broker-related positions will be collected by the stock exchanges
and provided to the market regulator shortly.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Needs to Improve Project Implementation: WB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh needs to address some
generic problems to improve its poor performance in project
implementation and an effective monitoring system should be
ensured, the World Bank said in a report published here today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the World Bank had discussed with the
Bangladeshi government some crucial generic issues during the
preparation of its 1996 country portfolio performance review.
</P>
<P>
But the Bangladeshi government, which receives an average
foreign aid of two billion U.S. dollars per year, has not taken
any resolute action to address these issues which continue to
affect project outcome, it said.
</P>
<P>
The issues include inadequate administrative authorities or
project directors and frequent staff rotation, delays in
procurement processing, lack of compliance with financial
reporting and audit requirements and delays in technical
assistance projects.
</P>
<P>
At the political level, the bank said, there has been often too
little involvement at the conceptual stage and consequently
ministers have rarely been the true champions of project conceived
and implemented.
</P>
<P>
The government should ensure a high degree of commitment by
taking a more active part at the project conceptualization and
design stage, the report added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian President for Reduction of Dependence on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President F. Chiluba
has urged his country to reduce dependence on donor charity in
its development, a source reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
"If our development is to have a solid and lasting foundation
it is essential and expedient that we reduce dependence on
donor charity," stated Chiluba when he officially opened the
First Session of the Eighth National Assembly here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said that the finance minister will present this
year's budget and the major thrust of the budget will be "living
within our means by reducing very drastically the budget's
dependence on external subventions."
</P>
<P>
He noted that it is important for the country to cede the
dependence syndrome for outside assistance.
</P>
<P>
However, Chiluba did not reject foreign aid. He said
that Zambia will for a long time to come continue to suffer
serious resource gaps and it will always welcome external
assistance when it is available to supplement the inadequate
internal accumulations.
</P>
<P>
But donor aid must be seen in the correct context of
engendering international cooperation towards global development.
</P>
<P>
"Zambia fully supports the United Nations system-wide special
initiative for Africa intended to mobilize international support
for development for the continent," the Zambian president said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
