<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 07:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kurdish Leader: PUK Desires Federal Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Leader of Iraq's Patriotic Union
of Kurdistan (PUK) Jalal Talabani has said that his party desired
a federal settlement with a "democratic" Iraq, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the Turkish Daily News published
here today, Talabani said that he did not make contacts with the
Iraqi government, although there had been indirect calls for a
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government kept wooing the PUK and sent a message
through Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeni Primakov for the start
of a dialogue with the PUK last year.
</P>
<P>
On the future of ties with Baghdad, Talabani said: "If
there is a democratic government, we will have a close federal
relation; if not, ours will be a looser bond within a
unified Iraq... Our laws will be in conformity with Iraqi
constitution."
</P>
<P>
The PUK leader said that he did not expect full democracy
from Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, but Iraq's form of
democracy "should be at least as that of Jordan or Kuwait."
</P>
<P>
The Iran-backed PUK fought with the Kurdish Democratic Party
(KDP), supported by the Iraqi government, in late August last
year, which led to U.S. air strikes against Iraqi military
targets.
</P>
<P>
The PUK and KDP then signed a peace deal on October 31,
1996, under mediation of the United States, Britain and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Northern Iraq has been occupied by Kurdish rebels since
the Gulf War in 1991, but it split into rival zones after
the KDP and the PUK began fighting each other in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
