<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Agricultural Union Warns of Anarchy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- With a high incidence of
crime and more and more people getting the law into their own
hands, South Africa is on the brink of crime anarchy, the local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
President of the South African Agricultural Union (SAAU) Chris
Du Toit said on Friday that "the country cannot afford another
six months on the road to crime anarchy and all sectors must now
work together to reverse the situation", according to
the Johannesburg-based daily The Citizen.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Pretoria, Du Toit said the high crime
rate was causing despair in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The point has now been reached where people are revolting and
taking the law into their own hands, something one cannot blame
them for," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
However, Du Toit said the crime problem has many facets,
adding policing is poor in many areas despite a greater will on
the part of the government to fight lawlessness.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the time has come for the entire South
African community to unite visibly in persuading the government
to act mercilessly to create effective deterrents to restore
law and order in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
