<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls on Arab Countries to Help Sudan Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has called on Arab
countries to help Sudan in its fighting against secessionist
rebels, saying the Khartoum government was facing a plot against
its territorial unity, local newspaper Jordan Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
"What brotherly Sudan is being exposed to is a conspiracy
aimed at the unity of its people and territory and this is a
matter that necessitates from Arab countries a united stance,"
Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Karim Kabariti was quoted as saying
in a statement, which was also carried by Jordan's national news
agency Petra.
</P>
<P>
Such support, Kabariti said, is "imperative to prevent the
exploitation of Sudan's circumstances and to confront the enemies
of the Arab Nation to foil the possibility of harming Sudan's
unity."
</P>
<P>
On Friday, a joint rebel force captured the town of Maban on
the southern front of the Blue Nile region as the Sudanese
government sent reinforcements to contain the rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
At present, the rebels are advancing towards Damazin, a
strategic town, which supplies the country's capital with 80
percent of its power, a rebels spokesman said. 
</P>
