<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM Rules Out Regional Military Showdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri has ruled out a full-blown military confrontation in
the Middle East, saying such an adventure was "two costly
for all sides including Israel," local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Beirut's Daily Star, the only English daily published in the
Lebanese capital, said that Hariri's remarks came at an Iftar, the
breakfast in the Moslem fasting month of Ramadan, at his
residence in West Beirut, which was attended by more than 700
guests.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the chances of war in the region, Hariri
said: "There is no war in the region."
</P>
<P>
"Two days ago (Egyptian) President Hosni Mubarak said the same
thing for war is very costly to all sides," he said, adding that
military means had been tried before but failed to work.
</P>
<P>
"In 1978 and again in 1982, the military solutions were
tried and did not work," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The only results were destruction and damage, killing and
bad reputation for the aggressors," Hariri added.
</P>
<P>
"We know that the Israeli army is capable of hitting
civilians and killing innocent people, damaging houses and
undermining this country's infrastructure, but the aggression did
not lead to a change in the political decision-making process
in Lebanon," Hariri said.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government has been plagued in recent weeks with
wide-spread rumors about an imminent war by Israel against
Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Hariri warned Israel against waging a war with Syria.
</P>
<P>
"When we refer to a regional military conflict, we are
talking about a war between Syria and Israel," Hariri said,
"a war with Syria means destruction to both Syria and Israel
and everyone will pay the price."
</P>
<P>
"The outlook is for peace and all the previous circumstances
and facts that favored war rather than peace are now behind us,"
the premier said.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that Israeli threats would not force a change
in Lebanon's policy toward the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
