<HEADLINE> Indian Industrial Growth Slows Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- A sharp fall in the growth of
infrastructure industries has led to a slowdown in industrial
growth during the first eight months of the current financial year
starting April 1, official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four industries recorded a mere five percent growth as
against 11 percent in the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
Cumulative growth in the infrastructure sector, accounting for
about 29 percent in the index of industrial production (IIP), fell
to 3.3 percent during April-November from 9.3 percent a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
Seven industries including crude petroleum, fertilizer, cloth
and jute recorded a negative growth as against just two industries
-- pig iron and copper cathodes.
</P>
<P>
The 18 major industries (excluding the infrastructure sector)
accounting for 21.6 percent in IIP, registered a 7.9 percent
growth against 14.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The crude petroleum industry was the worst hit with a 10
percent decline in production as compared with 11.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The crucial electricity sector grew by 3.2 percent compared
with 9.9 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
The best performance was recorded in sugar, cars, motor cycles
and three-wheelers growing 37.6 percent, 21 percent, 23.3 percent
and 33.9 percent respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
