<HEADLINE> Two-Line Hybrid Rice to Raise Farm Output in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- A new strain of two-line
hybrid rice, with a high potential for increased output, will give
grain production in China a major boost, said an expert from
central China's Hunan province.
</P>
<P>
Created by China's "Father of Hybrid Rice", the new strain,
compared with usual three-line varieties, can generate a higher
yield and can make use of manpower and material resources more
efficiently.
</P>
<P>
Hunan province planted 50,000 hectares of the new strain last
year and fulfilled a per hectare yield of more than 7,500
kilograms, up to 15 percent higher than three-line strains.
</P>
<P>
Hunan has taken the lead in the country in rice production for
several years. Annual rice output in the province is 26 billion
kilograms, and is expected to reach 30 billion kg in the year of
2000.
</P>
<P>
According to Yuan, the spread of the two-line hybrid rice
strain will play a positive role in helping the province fulfill
the target.
</P>
<P>
"Research on new strains of Chinese sorghum and oil-bearing
crops has also made breakthroughs through hybridization," said
Yuan.
</P>
<P>
A new strain of sorghum will raise its output to 7,500 kg for
each hectare. 
</P>
</TEXT>
