<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peruvian Rebels Free A Police Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian rebels occupying the
Japanese ambassador's residence released an ailing security chief
today at around 2 p.m. local time (1900 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Luis Valencia Hirano, head of the Delta special forces unit of
Peru's anti-terrorist police DINCOTE, was the first hostage freed
since the New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
The exhausted-looking Valencia was sent to a police hospital
accompanied by two Red Cross officials. The organization played a
go-between role linking together the Peruvian government and the
rebel Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA).
</P>
<P>
The release was followed by a statement from the Peruvian
government, saying it is ready to resume talks with the rebels but
refusing to free the rebels' imprisoned comrades.
</P>
<P>
Gunmen from MRTA broke into the diplomatic compound in the
evening of December 17 and held hostage more than 500 people, who
were attending a reception to mark Japanese Emperor Akihito's
birthday.
</P>
<P>
MRTA demanded the Peruvian government release its about 400
guerrilla comrades in jails, but was refused.
</P>
<P>
Domingo Palermo, the official negotiator, reiterated the
refusal today when he made the statement.
</P>
<P>
"As is publicly known, the Peruvian state is not going to
release the MRTA prisoners," he said.
</P>
<P>
MRTA international spokesman Isaac Velasco said the rebels
would never surrender without reaching their goals.
</P>
<P>
"We have said it a million times, we will say it again. We will
never give in," Velasco said at a press conference in the Danish
capital of Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
Palermo told a news conference he would meet leader of MRTA
Nestor Cerpa Cartolini in a building near the sieged compound. He
added that Cerpa would be transported to the site in a Red Cross
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
But so far rebels have not confirmed whether they would attend
the meeting. Previously they broke off a planned encounter with
Palermo because the government refused to discuss the release of
their comrades.
</P>
<P>
Rebels have freed most of the hostages and are still holding 73
persons in custody, including Peruvian President Alberto
Fujimori's younger brother and Foreign Minister Francisco Tudela.
</P>
<P>
Other hostages include Japanese ambassador Morihisa Aoki,
Japanese businessmen and Peruvian top officials.
</P>
<P>
A recent major poll shows that 93.2 percent of the subjects
believe the siege should be resolved through a peaceful way, and
88.2 percent say no rebels should be released from prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
