<HEADLINE> Former President Asks for Trial of Corrupt BNP Regime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The just-released former
Bangladeshi President Hussain Mohammad Ershad has asked Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina to put on trial the Bangladesh Nationalist
Party (BNP) regime for corruption.
</P>
<P>
"You (Hasina) will be identified as a promise-breaker if you
don't hold the trial," Ershad told a huge public meeting held
Friday in his hometown of Rangpur.
</P>
<P>
Hasina will be unable to continue her politics if she does not
keep her election pledge, said Ershad, who is also chairman of the
 Jatiya Party (JP).
</P>
<P>
Only with JP support, Hasina's Awami League (AL) won enough
seats to form the new government after the June 12 general
elections last year, turning the former ruling BNP into the
biggest opposition party in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
"We do not believe in the ideology of the AL," Ershad said. "We
supported it unconditionally to topple the BNP from power as the
AL emerged as the largest party against the BNP after polls."
</P>
<P>
The former president, who was deposed on December 6, 1990, and
sent to jail on charges of corruption, was released on bail on
January 9 this year.
</P>
<P>
Refuting the BNP allegation of obtaining the bail through an
entente with the AL, Ershad claimed that while he was in jail
after last year's general elections, the BNP wanted to make a deal
by withdrawing all cases against him and offering him the position
of prime minister. But he rejected the offer, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Even if I have to die, I'll never support the BNP, because
they oppressed me so much in jail," Ershad said amid thunderous
applause from his supporters who chanted "go ahead Ershad, we are
with you." 
</P>
</TEXT>
