<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stone Carving Booming in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, January 18 (Xinhua) -- A county in east China's Fujian
Province has become the biggest base for carved stone exports,
whose value surpassed two billion yuan (240 million US dollars)
last year.
</P>
<P>
The history of stone-carving in Hui'an County, the hometown of
many overseas Chinese, goes back to the Tang Dynasty (618-907),
and a well-known carving at the Sun Yat-sen Mausoleum in Nanjing,
a famous tourist attraction, is the work of the county's
stonemasons.
</P>
<P>
Hui'an has over 2,000 factories whose business is stone
carving, with an annual output value of more than 1.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 types of stone products have been exported to 30
countries and regions, including Japan and the US, said an
official with the local government.
</P>
<P>
The county places great importance on improving production
equipment, and has put more than 100 million yuan into this sector
in the past few years, he said.
</P>
<P>
It has also built a 35-km road with more than 1,000 stone
carvings and processing factories along it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
