<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Seize Another Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
seized on Friday another province and shot down a rival jet,
reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban forces overran the province of Kapisa, northeast of
the Afghan capital of Kabul, driving out the troops loyal to the
ousted Afghan government, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the militia also claimed to have shot down a rival
jet fighter plane in Charikar, north of Kabul and capital of
Parwan Province controlled by the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The jet belonging to the forces of northern Uzbek warlord Abdul
Rashid Dostum was raiding Taliban positions in Charikar, a Taliban
official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kapisa was seized a day after the Islamic militia recaptured
the strategic Bagram Airbase, about 50 kilometers north of Kabul,
and the key provincial capital of Charikar.
</P>
<P>
The militia, which seized Kabul on September 27 last year,
controls two-thirds of Afghan territory.
</P>
<P>
It faces combined military resistance from the ex-government
forces led by the ousted President Burhanuddin Rabbani's chief
military commander Ahmad Shah Masood and the troops of Dostum.
</P>
</TEXT>
