<HEADLINE> U.S. House Committee Votes to Reprimand Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- After two years of probe,
the U.S. House ethics committee voted tonight to reprimand Speaker
Newt Gingrich for admitted violations of House rules and called
for a financial penalty of 300,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions, ratified on a bipartisan vote of 7-1, would
permit Gingrich to retain his powerful post. A formal House vote
is scheduled for next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Gingrich said in advance he would submit to the
reprimand and the penalty.
</P>
<P>
"This is a tough penalty. I believe it is an appropriate
penalty," Nancy Johnson, the committee chairwoman, said as the
vote was announced. "It demonstrates that nobody is above the
rules."
</P>
<P>
On December 21, Gingrich admitted that he had violated House
rules, saying that he had failed to seek proper legal advice on
using tax-exempt projects to meet political goals, and he
acknowledged that "in my name and over my signature" inaccurate
statements had been submitted to the ethics committee.
</P>
<P>
If approved by the full House, the punishment would be the
sternest on a speaker since the ethics process was established
three decades ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
