<HEADLINE> Former Official Reveals India's Ties With CIA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Former Indian Foreign
Secretary J. N. Dixit has revealed that the Ministry of External
Affairs has had formal links with the American Central
Intelligence Agency (CIA) at least over the last 10 years, the
local newspaper The Pioneer reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The revelation adds a new dimension to the sensational Rattan
Sehgal "spy" case in which the senior Intelligence Bureau (IB)
officer was forced to retire for "unauthorized" meetings with two
"undercover" CIA agents recently.
</P>
<P>
Dixit said here on Friday that he himself formalized the
arrangement between the ministry and the U.S. government during
his tenure as foreign secretary. "This is not something that has
been announced publicly but we have been liaising with the CIA
ever since the Kashmir issue blew up."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Sehgal case and his "unauthorized" meetings
with two CIA agents, Dixit said the meetings were not a
clandestine operation as both U.S. officials were declared to the
government of India as liaison officers between the U.S.
intelligence agency and their Indian counterparts, the IB and its
research and analysis wing.
</P>
<P>
Sehgal, as chief of the IB counter-intelligence unit and
principal liaison officer, was in touch with the two CIA officials
in keeping with his routine work, he said. He called the meetings
an open liaison which he said has been converted into an espionage
drama.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
