<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Insists on Ratification of START-2 Before New Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States will
maintain its stance that the START-2 strategic arms treaty should
be ratified by the Russians before negotiations on further nuclear
cuts,
</P>
<P>
The point was made today by outgoing U.S. Secretary of State
Warren Christopher.
</P>
<P>
"Our position is that START-2 should be ratified and
implemented," said Christopher in a farewell interview with
international news agencies.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly our long-term goal is for additional arms control
agreements, but I don't think you can leapfrog over START-2, and
we've let the Russians know that we want to encourage them to find
a basis to go forward with START-2."
</P>
<P>
Under the START-2, or Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty, signed
in 1993 between the United States and Russia, the two countries
were to reduce their long-range nuclear arsenals by some two
thirds, to about 3,500 warheads apiece by 2003.
</P>
<P>
Russia now has about 7,600 nuclear warheads and the United
States has a little more than 9,100, according to the New
York-based Natural Resources Defense Council.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Duma (parliament) has so far resisted strong
pressure to ratify the treaty for reasons ranging from the cost of
implementing the treaty to concerns over U.S. missile defense
plans.
</P>
<P>
A recent U.S. Defense News report from Moscow said that until
Russian President Boris Yeltsin submits a detailed plan to the
Duma of all expenditures relating to the treaty, Russian
legislators will not begin consideration of the accord.
</P>
<P>
Russian opponents of START-2 argued that it was unfair because
Russia's nuclear deterrent was more reliant on land-based,
multiple-warhead missiles than that of the United States, which
was largely based on submarines and bomber aircraft, the Defense
News said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, most of the legislators directly link Russia's
reduction of nuclear arsenal with the NATO's plan to expand into
Eastern Europe, which Russians regard as posing threat to its
national security.
</P>
<P>
Russian Defense Committee Chairman Lev Rokhlin suggested that
Russia should scrap START-2 altogether and begin negotiations on a
START-3 treaty to cut the bilateral arsenals further and more
equitably.
</P>
<P>
However, U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said;
"We don't want to begin negotiations on START-3 until the Russian
 Duma has ratified START-2," when asked if there was any plan to
advance START-3 negotiations at all.
</P>
<P>
However, arms control experts were quoted by media reports
saying they understood that in order to spur the Duma to ratify
START-2, the administration was seriously considering making a
commitment that START-3 negotiations would begin immediately
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. President Bill Clinton and his Russian
counterpart, Boris Yeltsin, are set to meet in March, when they
would discuss the issue and hopefully get a deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
