<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Train Crash Inquiry to Take Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The official inquiry into last
weekend's fatal rail crash which killed eight people may not be
completed until June, Public prosecutor Alberto Grassi said today.
</P>
<P>
Grassi, who is heading the judicial inquiry into the
crash of the highspeed, tilting Pendolino train at Piacenza, said
he would appoint a commission of inquiry next week.
</P>
<P>
Its members would be "high level and absolutely impartial", he
said. But he intended to keep their names secret to protect them
from outside pressures.
</P>
<P>
He said he would not give the State Railways access to
material seized by police on his orders after the accident. It
included the train's trip recorder, the equivalent of a plane's
flight recorder.
</P>
<P>
Speculation about the cause of the crash has centered on the
possibility that the train entered a tight curve, just north of
Piacenza station, too fast.
</P>
<P>
Railway engineering professor Franco di Maio said today that
the radius of the curve was only 337 meters, compared to a minimum
of 2,500 meters of the high speed track between Rome and Florence.
</P>
<P>
He said that on the stretch of track just before the fatal bend
the train would have been traveling at about 190 kph.
</P>
<P>
The maximum allowed on the bend was 105 kph, and di Maio said
he calculated the train would leave the tracks above 155
kph. Media reports have suggested that the train's drivers, who
died in the crash, failed to slow down because they were eating
lunch at the time, but this hypothesis was dismissed as absurd by
the driver's union (COMU).
</P>
<P>
The COMU said it was calling a go-slow from next Monday to back
demands for talks with the railway management on a range of safety
issues.
</P>
<P>
These included maintenance of lines and rolling stock, the
conditions of signaling and safety installations, the abuse of
overtime, level crossings and the suitability of trains such as
the tilting Pendolino. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
