<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Zinc Industry Faces Production Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's zinc industry is
facing a decline in production capacity because of a mineral
shortage.
</P>
<P>
Padaeng Industry Plc, the only zinc producer in Thailand as
well as in the entire ASEAN region, faced pressure in terms of raw
material supply and higher power costs than those of rivals in
other countries, according to President of the company Teerachai
Riensubdee.
</P>
<P>
Padaeng, which used to be able to produce sufficient raw
materials to support its production, has now been forced to import
more raw materials, which has led to a considerably higher cost.
</P>
<P>
Teerachai said his company needed to step up efforts to lower
production costs and improve efficiency in order to gain a
competitive edge over rivals from Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's total zinc consumption last year was 123,000 metric
tons, of which Padaeng had a market share of 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that this year the demand will increase by 5.7
percent to 130,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Teerachai predicted that zinc prices in the world market this
year would likely pick up from current levels of 1,100-1,200 US
dollars a ton, because the global zinc stockpile has been
declining steadily.
</P>
<P>
The world zinc stockpile now totals about 480,000 tons, down
from a peak of 1.2 million tons in 1994, according to Teerachai.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tuberculosis Cases Soar in Kazakhstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh Minister of Public
Health Vasili Nikolaevich Devyatko warns that tuberculosis cases
have increased greatly in recent years, and now number 60,000.
</P>
<P>
He called today for immediate measures to battle the disease,
the Kazakh Telegraph Agency (KazTAG) reported.
</P>
<P>
Devyatko told a news briefing that the present death toll from
tuberculosis had doubled compared with several years ago. He
called on medical agencies to make efforts to eliminate the
disease.
</P>
<P>
He said urgent measures must be taken to get rid of diseases of
the respiratory tract, especially influenza, in order to prevent
tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
The Kazakh Tuberculosis Research Institute attributed the
increase in tuberculosis to economic stringencies. Funds allotted
to prevent the disease had decreased and patients had not received
timely treatment.
</P>
<P>
Devyatko said a special law to battle tuberculosis was being
drafted and a loan of 400,000 U.S. dollars would be used to buy
medical equipment to treat patients.
</P>
<P>
Japan, South Korea and other countries have also offered help
to Kazakhstan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Unit of Nuclear Station Returns to Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The first unit of Bulgaria's
six-unit Kozloduy Nuclear Power Station resumed operation today
after being appraised and checked out by western companies.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said the unit, with a capacity of 440,000 KW, was
endorsed today by the country's Committee of Peaceful Utilization
of Atomic Energy and is expected to feed into the national grid in
the next few days.
</P>
<P>
Kozloduy is Bulgaria's only nuclear power station, and is
located on the Danube riverside. It was forced to stop operation
because of doubts about its safety by western countries.
</P>
<P>
In December, it was concluded it would be able to work until
the year 2004, its designated expiry, by a watchdog group from the
Council of Europe, Germany's Siemens company, a U.S. company and
its Russian designer. The group examined samples of the unit's
outer metal cover.
</P>
<P>
Using generating units produced by the Leningrad electrical
machinery plant, the Kozloduy Power Station, the biggest in the
Balkan Peninsula, was set up in 1969.
</P>
<P>
The first two reactors went into operation in 1975. The next
three were established in the 1980s and the last one started to
work in September 1991.
</P>
<P>
Its generated energy accounted for 45 percent of the total
amount generated in Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
The first reactor had more than 160 improvements incorporated,
and the study of its outer metal cover indicated it could work
until the year 2006, Bulgarian experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
