<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, Canada Ink Deals on Satellite, Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has signed a contract
with Canada to buy a remote sensing small satellite worth 116
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The contract was signed Friday in front of Thai Prime Minister
Chavalit Yongchaiyudh and his Canadian counterpart Jean Chretien,
who is on a five-day visit to Thailand with a 450-member mission,
including over 350 business people.
</P>
<P>
The deal was inked after the Canadian side had agreed to delay
the payment and buy more Thai products in counter trade, as
Thailand is facing a current account deficit and is cutting back
public spending.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract, the payment will start from October of
1998, which is the first month of Thailand's fiscal 1999, instead
of January of 1998, and the counter-trade ratio in the deal will
be increased from the original 20 percent to a new 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Thai and Canadian businesses signed 55 contracts worth
just over 800 million dollars on Friday, the second day of
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien's five-day visit to
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
In terms of value, about 60 percent of the deals were
commercial contracts and the rest memorandums of understanding.
</P>
<P>
The deals covered a wide range of fields, including power,
petroleum, construction, electronic products distribution,
environment, steel, microwave technology, plastic coating and
fiberglass.
</P>
<P>
Ten other agreements were also signed on Friday between the two
governments and public sectors of the two countries involving
investment protection, cooperation in education, academics and the
environment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
