<HEADLINE> Colombia, Mexico Sign Anti-Drug Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Colombia and Mexico
signed three anti-drug agreements today following a bilateral
meeting held in this capital.
</P>
<P>
Colombian Foreign Relations Minister Maria Emma Mejia said the
agreements refer to judicial assistance, cooperation on detection
of drugs and psychotropic substances trafficking networks, and
thirdly, developing a pact of reciprocal assistance on the basis
of the United Nations convention signed in Vienna, December 20,
1996.
</P>
<P>
The Colombia-Mexico subcommission also studied key points for
the special session on the war against drugs to be held in the
United Nations in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Mejia said Colombia and Mexico reached an agreement to
intensify the development of trade, and on lines of credit between
the National Bank of Foreign Trade of Mexico, and the Andean
Development Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian minister and her Mexican counterpart, Jose Angel
Gurria, closed later in the day the Second Permanent Bilateral
Colombian-Mexican Commission. 
</P>
