<HEADLINE> More Vigor Urged in Romanian Crime Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu is calling for more effective measures against
organized crime -- in spite of great achievements made in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The president made his statement today at a meeting of the
Interior Ministry. He asked police not to make any allowances for
criminals.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, there were 320,000 crime cases across the country and
police made 220,000 arrests. They seized 11 ground-to-air missile
detonators, 1,668 guns, 318 kilograms of radioactive material, 15
kilograms of nuclear fuel and two and a half tons of explosives.
</P>
<P>
They also destroyed 200 crime syndicates which used forged
credentials in smuggling cigarettes, wine and coffee.
</P>
<P>
Romania has become one of main passages for international drug
smuggling. About 5,800 kilograms of drugs including 711 kilograms
of cocaine were seized in the country in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
