<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest Fish Dug out in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Archaeologists have stumbled on
a batch of fish fossils from tens of millions of years ago in
south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The archaeological team excavated the fossils from the basin
area of Tuolong, Dong'an and Mingjiang townships in Ningming
County, said Li Guoqing, a biological professor from Canada's
University of Alberta.
</P>
<P>
Li, also a member of the team which consists of Canadian
scholars and research fellows of the Guangxi Museum of Nature,
said the fish are similar to the Pacific herring, catfish and
carp. The longest fossil is more than 60 centimeters.
</P>
<P>
Scholars say the new find is significant for the classifying of
ancient osteichthyes and the study of geographical and
environmental conditions in ancient times within the Ningming
Basin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
