<HEADLINE> Moscow Mayor Disputes Sevastopol Authority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov has
repeated Russia's claim of authority over the controversial city
of Sevastopol, the main base of the Black Sea Fleet.
</P>
<P>
The Moscow Mayor, regarded as persona non grata in Ukraine,
made the remarks today when he arrived in Sevastopol to distribute
172 apartments to officers of the Black Sea Fleet.
</P>
<P>
"No document has ever confirmed that Sevastopol belongs to
Ukraine," Luzhkov said as he gave room keys to the officers.
</P>
<P>
Sevastopol was claimed by both Ukraine and Russia after the
collapse of the former Soviet Union in 1991. The dispute over the
division of the Black Sea Fleet and the status of Sevastopol have
hurt relations between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Luzhkov claimed Sevastopol was Russian territory in December
1996 when Russian and Ukrainian legislators fought a battle of
words over the city. He announced he would visit the city in
January 1997, and the Ukrainian Foreign Minister, Genady Udovenko,
wrote to persuade him not to come.
</P>
<P>
Luzhkov predicted Russia would win when the dispute was handed
over to the Permanent Court of Arbitration in The Hague. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
