<HEADLINE> Worry Over South Atlantic Radioactive Waste Transit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Uruguay,
Argentina, Brazil, and Chile expressed grave concern today over
risks associated with the transit of ships taking radioactive
wastes through the southern Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
The four countries in a joint statement made known their
concern about the pending arrival of a 40-ton plutonium cargo from
France bound for Japan.
</P>
<P>
The four said because of the danger implied by this
transportation means, they would adopt measures recognized by
international law to protect the health of their inhabitants, and
their marine ecological systems.
</P>
<P>
They said it was necessary to reinforce international
organizations with jurisdiction on the subject, the regulation of
transporting radioactive wastes and waste radioactive fuels.
</P>
<P>
They considered these regulations should also contemplate
guarantees not to pollute the marine environment, and on the
exchange of information about chosen routes.
</P>
<P>
Countries which transported radioactive wastes had the
obligation of communicating to the sea coast states emergency
plans for cases of disaster, a commitment to recover the
radioactive wastes and the payment of indemnities in cases of
injury or material damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
