<HEADLINE> Lanzhou Price Control Effective </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Latest statistics show that
Lanzhou, capital of northwest China's Gansu province, has made
great achievements in price control.
</P>
<P>
Its retail prices index was controlled to within six percent in
1996, lower than the country's average.
</P>
<P>
For the past two years, the city has been listed in a leading
position for its control of price increases compared with other
large and medium-sized cities.
</P>
<P>
Sky-rocketing prices had severely affected local economic
operations and residents' living standard.
</P>
<P>
To control price increases within an acceptable range, the
local government delayed carring out several price-adjustment
projects and set a ceiling prices and the floating range for daily
necessities, such as vegetables and grain.
</P>
<P>
The local government also worked out rules and regulations on
the price controls.
</P>
<P>
To keep prices of vegetables low, the local government launched
projects to increase vegetable production. In 1996 the city was 70
per cent self-supporting in its fresh vegetable supplies,
statistics show.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
