<HEADLINE> Indonesia Joins World's Longest Submarine Cable Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's state-owned PT.
IndoSat and 70 foreign telecommunications firms have signed an
agreement on a 1.3 billion U.S. dollar submarine cable network
project, an official of the IndoSat company said.
</P>
<P>
The network, called Sea-Me-We3, will link the Pacific Rim,
Southeast Asia, the Middle East and Europe, the local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
IndoSat's director of operations Ahmad Rivai said here Friday
that the 38,000 km Sea-Me-We3, to be completed in 1998, would
consist of three segments.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian part includes the 23,000-km Medan (North
Sumatra)-Singapore-Jakarta network tracing the Indian Ocean
towards the Middle East and Western European nations; the 5,000-km
Singapore-Jakarta-Australia network; And the 10,000-km
Jakarta-Singapore network linking Southeast Asia, the Pacific Rim,
Japan and China.
</P>
<P>
Rivai said the network would be the longest and largest
capacity submarine cable network in the world serving a combined
population of three billion people.
</P>
<P>
He said the Sea-Me-We3 has also applied synchronous digital
hierarchy technology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
