<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Wary of U.S. Push for ALCA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian government
has repeated its wariness about the United States proposal to
accelerate the creation of the Americas Free Trade Area (ALCA).
</P>
<P>
Brazil did not accept that a reduction of custom tariffs in the
ALCA should be discussed in advance, Jose Botafogo Gonzalves,
undersecretary for Economic Affairs, Integration, and Foreign
Trade, was quoted by the local press as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Brazil couldn't bear another round of tariff reductions that
would worsen the trade deficit, which stood at 5.2 billion
U.S. dollars last year, Gonzalves said.
</P>
<P>
The creation of the ALCA, a hemispheric free trade zone without
customs tariffs to be in force at the beginning of the year 2005,
will be discussed in May in Brazil by foreign trade ministers from
all the American continent countries except Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The Third Entrepreneurial Forum of the Americas will be held
simultaneously with the ministerial meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
