<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Currency Deposits Soar in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The foreign currency deposit
units (FCDU) accounts with the Philippines' commercial banks
reached a record 14.5 billion U.S. dollars by the end of 1996, a
local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
This record represents a 53 percent jump from the year-ago
level of 9.4 billion dollars, the Philippine Journal quoted
Philippine Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson as saying on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Though not officially counted as part of the Philippine
international reserves, the FCDU deposits represent a second layer
of foreign reserves for the country. Most of the FCDU accounts are
held by exporters, local companies with dollar earnings, and
families of overseas Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
The growing foreign currency deposits can be attributed to
increased exports, foreign investments and remittances from
Filipino workers overseas.
</P>
<P>
The FCDU accounts, mostly in U.S. dollar deposits, are held by
the 48 commercial banks operating in the country.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the record FCDU deposits, the Philippines also
registered a record gross international reserves of 11.8 billion
dollars in 1996, 4 billion dollars higher than the figure for
1995, the newspaper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
