<HEADLINE> Helms Urges Suspension of Aid to South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Senate Foreign
Relations Committee Chairman Jesse Helms today asked the Clinton
administration to suspend aid to South Africa if it goes ahead
with plans to sell weapons components to Syria.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Clinton, Helms said: "I respectfully urge that
you refrain from waiving the provisions of the Anti-terrorism
Act."
</P>
<P>
"The government of South Africa should understand that ... a
significant amount of U.S. foreign aid to South Africa will be cut
off," if its 650-million-U.S.-dollar military deal with Syria goes
through, he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, the State Department threatened to cut off
its 120-million-dollar aid to Pretoria if South Africa ignores
U.S. warning.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, South African President Nelson Mandela rejected
pressures from the United States to halt the contract of supplying
modern firing control systems to Syria.
</P>
<P>
"There is no country anywhere in the world that is going to
dictate to South Africa," the South African president said. "What
we decide will be in the interest of South Africa and South Africa
alone."
</P>
<P>
Helms, a staunch supporter of Israel, said: "Syrian acquisition
of the state-of-art military hardware runs counter to longstanding
U.S. national security interest in the region (of the Middle East)
and represents a significant new threat to Israel." 
</P>
</TEXT>
