<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Companies in the Costa Rican tax-free zone will
invest in the country 50 million U.S. dollars between May of 1996
and May of 1997, Foreign Trade Ministry sources predicted.
</P>
<P>
The estimate does not include the 300-500 million dollar
investments to be made by Intel, the biggest industrial company in
the world which produces parts for computers.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaragua registered in 1996 a 12 percent inflation,
two points over the government's target and 0.8 percent higher
than 1995.
</P>
<P>
One of the causes for the higher rate was the rise in the
international oil prices, which in turn raised fuel prices and
prices of other commodities.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Uruguayan meat output will reach 893,000 tons
this year, a 5.9 percent increase over 1996, the Livestock,
Agriculture, and Fishing Ministry forecast.
</P>
<P>
Meat exports will reach 225,000 tons, 340 million dollars in
value.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- The Colombian Banking Superintendency
revealed that at the end of October, 1996, there were 1,686,656
credit cards in use with a 1.093 billion dollar portfolio, of
which 707 million dollars was handled by Credibanco-Visa, 257
million dollars by Mastercard, and 128 million dollars by the
"other cards" classification.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The 1996-1997 season in Argentine agriculture
output reached an unprecedented volume of 56,200,000 tons,
surpassing by 22.7 percent the tonnage registered during the
1994-1995 season, when 45.8 million tons were produced, the
Agriculture, Livestock, and Fishing Ministry announced.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The budget for the Panama Canal this year is 550
million dollars, a figure to be maintained after the year 2000,
when the country will have full control of the interoceanic
waterway.
</P>
<P>
It would be necessary to hire more Panamanians to work in the
Canal, because the use and benefits of the Canal were considered
to be part of a global framework adapted to the needs of the
country, said Ricaurter Vasquez, comptroller of the waterway
commission.
</P>
<P>
About 850 million dollars will be invested during the next
eight years for the modernization of the Canal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
