<HEADLINE> Italy to Send Police for Hebron Observer Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 17 (Xinhua) -- A contingent of 31 Italian
security police will join the international observer force in
Hebron in early February, the Italian Ministry of Defense said
today.
</P>
<P>
The Italians will join colleagues from Norway, Sweden,
Denmark, Switzerland and Turkey in a 140-strong force known as the
Temporary International Presence in Hebron (TIPH2).
</P>
<P>
The force will be commanded by a Norwegian, with Colonel Pietro
Pistolese, leader of the Italian contingent, as his second in
command, said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The observers will monitor compliance with the agreements
between Israel and the Palestinians and try to help create
conditions for restoring public confidence.
</P>
<P>
The ministry stressed that the Hebron force would be unarmed.
Its mission is to patrol alongside Palestinian police, who had the
responsibility for security in the city.
</P>
<P>
The ministry explained that the Italian contingent had been
requested by both Israel and the Palestinians, "in recognition of
the efforts made by two previous missions and the appreciation
received."
</P>
<P>
The commitment should be seen in the context of increasing
Italian military participation in peace missions abroad, the
ministry noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
