<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austrians Win Team Title in World Luge Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Austria won the team title as
the 32nd World Luge Championships kicked off in Igls, Austria on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Defending doubles champions Tobias and Markus Schiegl paced
Austria for the team title on 145 points, followed by Germany with
139 points.
</P>
<P>
Italy took third at 124, the United States finished fourth with
122 and Russia was fifth in the field of 18 teams with 83 points.
</P>
<P>
The Schiegls' one-heat time of 40.025 seconds also shattered
the previous track mark by 0.25 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Stefan Krausse and Jan Behrendt and World Cup leaders
Chris Thorpe and Gordy Sheer of the United States, all beat the
previous record.
</P>
<P>
The Germans were just 0.008 seconds behind the Austrians with a
time of 40.033. Thorpe and Sheer, winners of three World Cup
races, took third in 40.104.
</P>
<P>
Austria's charge was helped by their women players Andrea
Tagwerker and Angelika Neuner who placed 1-2 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Tagwerker bettered the women's course record in 40.110 seconds,
while Neuner was clocked in 40.145. Lillehammer Olympic champion
Gerda Weissensteiner of Italy finished third in 40.225.
</P>
<P>
In the men's solo track, the 1988 Olympic champion Jens Mueller
of Germany set a record of 48.833 seconds, with Austria's
defending world champion Markus Prock on second in 48.934 and 1992
and 1994 Olympic champions Georg Hackl of Germany third in 48.980.
</P>
<P>
The world championships will resume Saturday with the women's
and doubles events. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
