<HEADLINE> Bosnian Authorities Urged to Give Information on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 17 (Xinhua) -- President of the International
Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) Cornelio Sommaruga on Friday
urged Bosnian authorities to provide information on the missing
persons.
</P>
<P>
During the 43-month-long war in Bosnia, a total of 18,000
missing persons have been listed, and a majority of them are
probably dead, but the authorities must at least provide
information on them, Sommaruga told reporters in Serb city Banja
Luka after meeting with Serb President Biljana Plavis.
</P>
<P>
"The problem of persons missing in the civil war is a real
humanitarian tragedy," and the authorities of both entities in
Bosnia -- Republika Srpska and Muslim-Croat federation -- have the
greatest responsibility for resolving this problem, Tanjug news
agency quoted the ICRC president as saying.
</P>
<P>
Describing Friday's meeting with Serb leaders as very useful,
Sommaruga, who is in Bosnia on a several-day visit, said the
humanitarian situation was very difficult in both entities, and he
had discussed the issue with Plavsic the means of resolving
humanitarian problems.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic said after the meeting that she had been impressed by
Sommaruga's report to the London conference and that the same
problems were on the agenda of Friday's meeting, including all
aspects of the humanitarian tragedy in the region.
</P>
<P>
Both entities have claimed that thousands of their people went
missing during the war and charged the other side for
responsibility. ICRC's regional offices in the former Yugoslavia
are responsible for collecting and passing information on missing
persons between the two entities. So far, more than 500 missing
persons have been identified. 
</P>
</TEXT>
