<HEADLINE> Gingrich Agrees to Reprimand, $300,000 Penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, admitted ethics violations are proving to be costly
errors, today agreed to submit to a reprimand by the House and pay
300,000 U.S. dollars of penalty as punishment for violating House
rules.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich insists his breaches, including providing false
information to the ethics panel, were unintentional. But he admits
they "discredited" the House and has agreed to the recommended
penalty.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation would enable Gingrich to retain his title as
speaker.
</P>
<P>
During a long-awaited public hearing into the case, special
counsel James M. Cole laid out the findings of his year-long
investigation. Cole said Gingrich used tax-deductible funds for
two activities with "substantial partisan political aspects to
them" including a college course Gingrich taught.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich admitted on December 21 that he had violated House
rules. He said he had failed to seek proper legal advice on using
tax-exempt projects to meet political goals, and he acknowledged
that "in my name and over my signature" inaccurate statements had
been submitted to the ethics committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
