<HEADLINE> Tudjman Says Croatia Wants Balkan Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Croatian President Franjo
Tudjman said on friday his country would constructively help
implement the Dayton peace plan and the Muslim-Croat federation
accord but would not join the Balkan or southeast European unions.
</P>
<P>
Croatia "does not wish to enter into any Balkan or southeast
European unions or associations," although it hopes to develop
good relations with its neighbors, Tudjman said in Zagreb at a
traditional New Year meeting with the diplomatic corps in the
Croatian capital, according to Tanjug news agency report.
</P>
<P>
Croatia was willing, however, to heed the recommendations of
the European Union and the United States and review concrete
measures for cooperation in the region, the president added.
</P>
<P>
Tudjman added that the year 1996 had been the first year of
peace in Croatia, and conditions existed for the current trend to
continue in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Croatia's principal state policy target would be to bring to
completion the peaceful reintegration of the Serb region of
Eastern Slavonia into Croatia, he said.
</P>
<P>
Eastern Slavonia, located in the northeastern Croatia bordering
Yugoslavia, is now under U.N administration. The majority of the
local population are Serbs who fear possible retaliation or
discrimination after the Croatian government resumes power in that
region in July of 1997. 
</P>
