<HEADLINE> Kunming Starts River Purification Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Kunming City in southwest
China's Yunnan Province has started a large-scale operation to
clean up the water of five "smelly rivers" that run through urban
areas in the provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
The city government has decided to complete the work by the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 1,000 local people cleared over 20 tons of garbage and
floating waste from the Panlong River in just one day this week.
</P>
<P>
The city has vowed to have all the floating garbage along the
river banks moved before the coming Spring Festival which starts
on February 7.
</P>
<P>
The five rivers, including the Panlong River, Mingtong River
and Daguan River, became smelly some years ago as more than 50
tons of waste water were discharged daily, and piles of garbage
were dumped along the banks of the rivers.
</P>
<P>
Pollution of Dianchi Lake, a famous scenic spot in the city, is
also worsened as the five rivers flow into the lake.
</P>
<P>
The Dianchi Protection Committee and the city's waste water
discharge company urged units or enterprises along the river banks
to offer money or send employees to work on the river clean-up
operation.
</P>
<P>
In a related effort, the city is to build a project to transfer
waste water from the Panlong River into a waste water disposal
plant, cutting waste water discharged into Dianchi Lake by 10 tons
a day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Corrects Mistake in Report on Nazi Gold Bought by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Foreign and Commonwealth
Office of the United Kingdom published today a new version of its
report on Nazi gold that Switzerland bought in 1946, correcting an
error in its 1996 report, the Swiss Federal Department of Foreign
Affairs announced in the Swiss capital of Bern.
</P>
<P>
In the old report published in September, 1996, the British
Foreign Office claimed that the Swiss National Bank (SNB) paid 500
million U.S. dollars for gold seized by German Nazis from their
occupied countries. The new report said that the amount which the
SNB had paid was 500 million Swiss francs.
</P>
<P>
In 1946 when the transactions finished, one U.S. dollar was
worth 4.3 Swiss francs. At present, one dollar is about 1.3
francs.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss government is satisfied with Britain's correction of
the mistake but regrets that it has been condemned by the
international press based only on inaccurate information, said the
Swiss task force for the investigation of whereabouts of Nazi
gold.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the task force today handed over a list containing
the names of 53 Polish account holders to the Polish Ambassador in
Switzerland. The Polish authorities have committed themselves to
make the list public as soon as possible in order to locate those
entitled to restitution, according to a press release by the task
force.
</P>
<P>
The list concerns account holders whose assets were transferred
in 1975 to the Polish government in line with the Swiss-Polish
Compensation Agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
