<HEADLINE> Small Plane Crash Kills Two in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- A small plane crashed in New
Hampshire today after an untrained girl failed to control the
aircraft after the pilot had apparently passed out from carbon
monoxide fumes, killing both of them, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Federal Aviation Administration controllers tried to talk the
girl into a safe landing after the pilot fell unconscious this
afternoon, possibly due to carbon monoxide fumes in the cabin, but
they lost contact with the plane just before it reached a airport
in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
The drama began shortly after the private plane took off from
Republic Airport on New York's Long Island at 11:50 a.m. (1650
GMT). The FAA learned the plane was in trouble just after noon. It
crashed 40 kilometers northeast of Concord, New Hampshire at 1:30
p.m. (1830 GMT). 
