<HEADLINE> Former Bosnian Serb Vice President in Critical Condition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Former Bosnian Serb
Vice-President Nikola Koljevic was under operation at Belgrade's
military medical academy hospital late on Friday, but his
condition is still extremely critical, a hospital source said.
</P>
<P>
Hospital Press Chief Col. Radoslav Svicevic said "Koljevic was
brought into the hospital in a very serious condition, but with
his vital organs functioning."
</P>
<P>
Koljevic, who shot himself in the head in a suicide attempt
during the previous night, arrived accompanied by his wife and by
SFOR French battalion doctor Philippe Bauer, Tanjug news agency
quoted Svicevic as saying. It is still unknown why he want to
take his own life.
</P>
<P>
Svicevic said Koljevic had been rushed to the academy hospital
from Sokolac in the Serb Republic by an NATO-led Stabilization
Force (SFOR) helicopter which took off with much difficulty
because of poor weather.
</P>
<P>
Koljevic, 60, was a university professor of literature before
he became vice-president of the Republika Srpska in early 1992. He
stepped down last Summer after the other Serb Vice-president
Biljana Plavsic took power from the former Serb President Radovan
Karadzic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
