<HEADLINE> Canada's Foreign Trade Rise in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Canada's international
merchandise trade moved ahead in November, with exports up 5.7
percent and imports up 4.7 percent, Statistics Canada reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Exports rose to a level of 16.5 billion U.S. dollars.
Automotive exports accounted for the bulk of the increase,
regaining two-thirds of the losses related to October's General
Motors strike.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the automotive sector, exports grew 0.7 percent in
November, the federal fact-gathering agency said.
</P>
<P>
In November, imports rose to a record of 15.2 billion dollars.
A surge in aircraft purchases and a rebound in auto parts imports
were the main sources of growth.
</P>
<P>
Since exports grew faster than imports, the November trade
surplus increased to 1.3 billion dollars from 1.1 billion in
October.
</P>
<P>
A stronger trade balance with the United States was responsible
for most of the increase, the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
