<HEADLINE> Brittan Warns over Anti-European Mood in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission
Vice-President Sir Leon Brittan warned here today that the surging
anti-European mood in Britain could eventually make the country
isolated in the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Speaking during a brief visit to London earlier today, Brittan
said that the concept of flexibility to allow some EU members
forge ahead in some areas could result in Britain becoming
increasingly isolated in the 15-nation block.
</P>
<P>
Brittan, a former British Conservative minister in the 1980s,
warned British politicians not to "damage Britain by engaging in a
Dutch auction of Euro-scepticism."
</P>
<P>
The anti-European sentiment is gathering momentum across
Britain with 38 percent of Britons wanting to quit the EU,
signaling a marked increase of anti-European feelings, according
to a recent opinion survey.
</P>
<P>
Brittan, who has been a EU commissioner since 1989, noted that
he had conveyed his warning to British Prime Minister John Major
and opposition Labor leader Tony Blair, calling on them not to
launch an anti-European election campaign.
</P>
<P>
He also made it clear that he did not expect Major to rule out
the possibility of joining the single European currency in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"I don't believe there will be any change in the present
(wait-and-see) formula, and I think it would be unwise to make
such a change," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
