<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Syrian Vice-President Discuss Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
held talks here this evening with visiting Syrian Vice-President
Abdul-Halim Khaddam and Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara on
suspended Mideast peace talks.
</P>
<P>
During their two-hour talks, the Syrian vice-president conveyed
a letter to Mubarak from Syrian President Hafez Al-Assad, which
dealt with the current situation in the Arab world and the Middle
East peace process, the Egyptian Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed the latest developments in the
Middle East region and means of strengthening joint Arab actions.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal El-Ganzouri and Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Israel and Syria were suspended last March
after four suicide bombings in Israel killed over 60 people.
Syria has demanded the return of the Golan Heights, captured by
Israel in the 1967 Mideast war, as a precondition for peace.
</P>
<P>
However, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu has said the
Golan Heights are crucial to Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians signed an agreement Tuesday to
redeploy Israeli troops in the West Bank town of Hebron and much
of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, which is the first Arab country to make peace with
Israel, now plays a leading role in brokering peace in
Arab-Israeli talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
