<DOCNO> XIE19970118.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rubin: Constitutional Balanced-budget Amendment Risky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin said today that approval of a balanced-budget
amendment to the Constitution would expose the U.S. economy to
"unacceptable risks."
</P>
<P>
In testimony before the U.S. Senate Judiciary Committee, he
said a constitutional amendment to achieve the aim of balanced
budget was the wrong approach to take and would have serious
consequences.
</P>
<P>
"A balanced-budget amendment could turn slowdowns into
recessions and recessions into more severe recessions or even
depressions," Rubin said. "It could prevent us from dealing
expeditiously with emergencies such as natural disasters or
military threats."
</P>
<P>
The amendment "is a threat to our economic health, will expose
our economy to unacceptable risk and should not be adopted," Rubin
told the committee.
</P>
<P>
He said that U.S. Congress and the White House are very close
to an agreement that would achieve a balanced budget by 2002 and
that this was the proper approach to take.
</P>
<P>
Rubin's testimony marked the U.S. Government's opening salvo in
a campaign to defeat the constitutional amendment in the U.S.
Congress this year.
</P>
<P>
In comments to reporters on November 12 last year, President
Clinton had appeared to soften his longtime opposition to the
amendment, saying that he would consider the idea if it contained
an "escape hatch" for the economic recessions.
</P>
<P>
But Rubin and other government officials made corrections
quickly the next day. They said that Clinton's remarks had not
represented a change of position and the president still intended
to fight the amendment.
</P>
<P>
A constitutional amendment requires passage by two-thirds of
both houses of the U.S. Congress and then approval by
three-quarters of the state legislatures.
</P>
<P>
In the last Congress, a constitutional balanced-budget amendment
received the necessary votes in the U.S. House of Representatives
but failed to clear the Senate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
