<HEADLINE> Maurice Strong Named as Senior Advisor on U.N. Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Canadian businessman
Maurice Strong has been named as senior advisor to
Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
The nomination was made on Thursday and confirmed today by U.N.
spokesman Fred Eckhard, who said that Strong, currently an advisor
to the World Bank in Washington, would help Annan "coordinate
efforts to redesign the organization for the future.
</P>
<P>
He said Annan had called for a preliminary meeting on Saturday
with Strong and Joseph Cornnor, the Under-Secretary-General for
Administration and Management.
</P>
<P>
Annan intends in the first six months of his term to come with
a plan for restructuring the world body to make it relevant in the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
Strong, a former Calgary oil executive, served as U.N.
undersecretary-general for the Earth Summit conference on the
environment in 1992. He is one of a small number of senior staff
and advisers who work for nominal salaries. His annual salary is
said to to one U.N. dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
