<HEADLINE> European Shares All End at Record Highs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Stock markets in London, Paris
and Frankfurt all surged ahead and ended the week at new record
levels Friday, boosted by Wall Street's advance and the dollar's
surge to its highest level since June 1994.
</P>
<P>
Share prices in London ended the week on a high note at a new
all-time closing high of 4,207.7, 10.2 points up on the day and a
rise of 151.10 points on the week, and the first time it has burst
through the 4,200 barrier. The FTSE had earlier today peaked at
4,218.4.
</P>
<P>
Falling domestic bond yields, firm futures and gilts, and the
Dow Jones move above the 6,800-level all helped to boost the
market, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares broke through the magical
3,000-points barrier, ending up 8.06 points at 3,001.37, boosted
by a 30-month record high for the dollar, which was particularly
favorable for German exporters. The DAX-30 index was 67.98 points
higher on last Friday.
</P>
<P>
French stocks had earlier today surged to a peak of 2,426.13
before closing at a fresh record high as the market continued its
bullish run, with the CAC-40 index up 17.33 points at 2,425.10, a
gain of 97.6 points on the week.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the surge was fuelled by fresh liquidities and a
firmer dollar.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index of leading British shares closed 10.2
points higher at 4,207.7. Frankfurt's DAX-30 index ended up 8.06
points at 3,001.37. In Paris, the CAC-40 index finished 17.33 up
at 2,425.10.  
</P>
</TEXT>
