<HEADLINE> Clinton Honors Dole with Presidential Medal of Freedom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today awarded his presidential campaign rival, former Senate
Republican leader, Bob Dole the Presidential Medal of Freedom for
his service in Congress and heroism in World War II.
</P>
<P>
Dole was honored for his service in World War II and 35 years
in Congress. Accepting the honor, Dole said, "No one can claim to
be equal to this honor, but I will cherish it as long as I
live..."
</P>
<P>
Dole, 73, was gravely wounded in Italy during the war. He won a
Purple Heart for heroism. After the war, Dole returned home and
served in the Kansas statehouse, win seats in the House, then
Senate, and finally hold the GOP Senate leadership for a record 12
years.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, Clinton said of Dole, "Son of the soil,
citizen, soldier and legislator, Bob Dole understands the American
people, their struggles, their triumphs and their dreams."
</P>
<P>
On the eve of his second term beginning on Monday, Clinton
honored Dole as a gesture of seeking a climate of reconciliation
with Republicans.
</P>
<P>
Today's ceremony also served as an occasion to unveil the
design for a World War II monument in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
